[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/fr/bataille_b1_bis]
Development of this tank began in 1921. It’s main purpose was supposed to be infantry support. The tank entered service in March 1934 В1. Since 1935 five companies, - Renault, FCM, Schneider, FAMH and АРХ, - were producing these tanks. When production ended on June 15, 1940 about 403 such tanks had been manufactured.

The В1 bis were engaged in combat on the French Front from May to June 1940 where they earned their reputation as invulnerable tanks, since no German tank or antitank gun could ever penetrate their armor.
After France was occupied, the Germans captured about 161 В1 bis tanks in working condition which later received the designation В2 740(f).

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/fr/hotchkiss_h35]
The Hotchkiss, the main French light tank was designed by Hotchkiss in 1934. About 1,000 units were manufactured from 1935 to 1940.
By the beginning of the war in May 1940 the French Army counted some 821 Н35/38/39 vehicles.
The light Н35 tanks served in separate tank battalions assigned to field armies.
In the cavalry, the Н35/38/39 tanks were in service with Mechanized Light Divisions, Cavalry Light Divisions and Mechanized Infantry Divisions. 
The 1st and the 2nd Mechanized Light Divisions counted 40 H35 tanks each. The 1st and the 2nd Cuirassier Regiments forming part of the 3rd Mechanized Light Divisions were equipped with the same number of the Н39 tanks, and 60 H35 units served in the 11th Dragoon Regiment. Four of the five Light Cavalry Divisions in the Armored Cavalry Reconnaissance Regiment had 12 H35 tanks each at their disposal and the fifth counted 12 H39 tanks. 
One tank squadron of 16 H35 was deployed in North Africa. The 342nd and the 351st tank companies equipped with H35 and Н39 tanks saw combat action in Norway (1940).
After France suffered defeat in 1940 about 600 Н35/39 tanks were captured by German troops. The tanks were repaired and modified: German radios were installed and the commander’s cupola was replaced with a double hatch. Under the designation PzKpfw 38H 735 (f) the tank was used in the Wehrmacht and the SS. 

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/fr/renault_amr_35zt]
An improved variant of the AMR 33. Renault Co., the developer of the tank, started its production in 1935. Some 200 units were manufactured before 1940.
The AMR 35ZT was the first mass-produced version. The tank had a riveted hull and turret with sloped armor. 
By September 1939, 129 AMR 35,10 AMR 35ZT2 and AMR 35ZT3 were deployed. They were used in the 1st and the 4the Dragoon Regiments of the 1st and the 2nd Mechanized Cavalry Divisions, 69 machines in each. The 7th (the 1st DIM) and the 6th (the 3rd DIM) Tank Reconnaissance Groups were equipped with four AMR 35 tanks, versions ZT2 and ZT3, each. After France was defeated most tanks of that type were captured by German troops and used by the Wehrmacht as transports for 80 mm mortars.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/fr/renault_ft17]
Until the mid-1930s the French tank fleet was based on the Renault FT-17 tank and its different modifications. It appears to be the first tank in the world with a fully rotating turret. The tank was produced since 1917 by Renault, Berliet, Schneider and Delauney-Belleville. In total some 7,820 units were manufactured.
The hull and the multi-sided turret of the Renault FT-17 were riveted. Some tanks had a ‘tail’ which enabled them to overcome wide ditches and trenches.
By 1940 the French Armored forces had 7 dedicated tank battalions (the 11th, the 18th, the 29th, the 30th, the 31st, the 33rd, the 36th ВСС) equipped mainly with FT-18 tanks, about 63 tanks in each. Also, three dedicated FT-18 companies (the 343rd , the 344th , the 350th Cie.A) were formed having about 10 tanks each. The rest of the tanks of this type were stored in depots.
Before the outbreak of the war, FT-17 (FT-18) tanks were exported to Afghanistan, Belgium, Brazil, Greece, Holland, Spain, Italy, Poland, USA, Finland, Czechoslovakia, Yugoslavia and Japan.
The FT-17 and FT-18 tanks serving in the Polish Army took part in the war against the USSR in 1920 and against Germany in the autumn of 1939. Also, these vehicles fought in France against German troops. However, after the French Campaign was finished, the FT tanks captured by the Germans were used in police units and for guarding airfields, and served under the designation PzKpfw 18R 730 (f).

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/fr/renault_r35]
In 1934 the company Renault, following an order from the Army, developed the light tank R35. This tank was in serial production from 1935 to 1940. During this period Renault delivered about 1,070 tanks to the French Army and exported some other 560 units.
The Renault R35 became the first version to enter serial production. Later on, a conversion, the R39 with a long-barrel 37 mm SA38 gun was developed. Then a model followed with a new suspension system by AMX and a similar gun to that of the R39. The tank was designated R40.
The French Army used the R35, R39 and R40 tanks in all theatres of operations. In May 1940 a total of 945 units were deployed in Europe, of which 810 served in dedicated tank battalions and 135 were allocated to the 4th Tank Division of the Reserve (DCR).
Several colonial units in North Africa were equipped with R35 tanks. The 68th Tank Battalion was deployed in Syria, the 63rd and 62nd Battalions served in Tunisia and Algeria respectively. R35 were also in service in Poland, Yugoslavia, Romania and Turkey.
After the defeat of France in 1940, about 800 R35 tanks fell into German hands. Germans used most of the tanks for training purposes and some of them, after removing the turret, were rebuilt into artillery tractors for 150 mm howitzers and 210 mm mortars.  
The Renault R35 took part in combat actions in the French 5th Dragoon Regiment during the liberation of France in 1944-1945.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/fr/somua_s35]
The medium tank Somua S35 was designed by the company Somua in 1935 by request of the French Cavalry Command. About 500 tanks were manufactured between 1935 and 1940.
Before 1940, S35 medium tanks were delivered to French units exclusively and never exported to other countries. The Mechanized Cavalry Regiments of three Mechanized Light Divisions were equipped with these tanks. The S35 served in the 4th Cuirassier, the 18th Dragoon, the 13th and the 29th Dragoon, the 1st and the 2nd Cuirassier Regiments. In Tunisia the 6th Light Cavalry Division counted 50 S35 tanks.
After the defeat of France about 300 S35 tanks were captured by the Germans, who reequipped the commander’s cupola with a double hatch and gave the tank the designation PzKpfw 35S 739 (f). Later these tanks were used on the Eastern front in the 211th Tank Battalion and in Crimea in the 204th Tank Regiment. In Normandy, the 100th Tank Reserve Battalion and the 206th Tank Battalion were partly reequipped with tanks of this type and fought against the Allies. In 1941, Germans converted about 60 tanks into artillery tractors.
In 1944 during combat operations in France the  21st Tank Division of the Wehrmacht counted 23 S35 tanks and 17 S35 tanks served in the French Forces of the Interior (FFI), liberating the country.
The S35 tank was a quite menacing rival for German tanks and may be considered the best French tank.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/ger/klpzbfwg_i]
In 1935, a commander tank designated Kleiner Panzerbefehlswagen I A (also known as Sd.Kfz.265) was designed from the Pz.Kpfw.I Ausf.A. The turret was replaced with a superstructure which could hold two crew members (a commander and a radio operator) and two radio stations. Six such vehicles were produced in late 1935.
In 1936, an upgraded version of the tank was designed based on the Pz.Kpfw.I Ausf.B chassis. Apart from the new chassis the tank designated Kleiner Panzerbefehlswagen I B differed in its standard armament (one MG-34 7.92 mm machine gun) and a redesigned superstructure. Two series of the Kleiner Panzerbefehlswagen I B were produced with a total number of 200 vehicles. The tanks were upgraded before the Polish campaign of 1939 and received a FuG 8 radio station, the frame aerial being replaced by a stub antenna. 
Like most commander vehicles, the Kleiner Panzerbefehlswagen I B should not be treated as a front combat unit. Commander tanks were supposed to stay back and to coordinate the tank groups, while their own armament provided protection only against enemy infantry.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/ger/pz_35t]
In 1934, Skoda designed a SU light tank which was used as the basis for a new S-II-a. In the following year the tank was supplied to the Czechoslovakian Army under the designation LT vz.35. The tank was produced at the Skoda and CKD factories, and a total of 298 were produced.
After the infamous Munich Agreement Germany annexed the Czech territories and Moravia in March 1939, and the Germans received 218 LT vz.35 tanks, while Slovakia received another 79 tanks of this type. In the German Army the tank was designated as Pz.Kpfw.35(t).
The engine of the Pz.Kpfw.35(t) was mounted in the rear along with the transmission. Unlike German tanks, Czech tanks had riveted hulls and turrets. This made the assembly easier but if the tanks were hit by shells, the rivet heads would often break off and injure the crew. The primary armament of the Pz.Kpfw.35(t) was the 37 mm Skoda A-3 vz.34 gun (German designation 37 mm Kw.K 34(t)) located in the turret. Coupled with the gun was the 7.92 mm ZB vz.35 or ZB vz.37 coaxial machine gun (MG 35(t) and MG 37(t) respectively), and another machine gun was fitted in the front armor plate in a special ball mount. The running gear was characteristic of Skoda’s tanks and consisted of eight dual road wheels, which were blocked in pairs and assembled into two bogies with leaf springs. Another dual wheel was located between the front bogie and the idler. This design enabled smooth running. 
The Germans were using the Pz.Kpfw.35(t) from the Polish campaign until the winter of 1941. Having similar weight the Czech tank was superior to its German peer Pz.Kpfw.II almost in all parameters and was very similar to the early versions of the Pz.Kpfw.III. The Pz.Kpfw.35(t) was taken as a basis for the design of the Befehlswagen 35(t) commander tank and the artillery tractor – Artillerie Schlepper 35(t).

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/ger/pz_38t]
The development of Pz.Kpfw.38(t) started in 1935 when the firm Ceskomoravska Kolben Danek (CKD) was hired by the Iranian Government to design a tank with a 37 mm gun and two machine guns. The tank designated Praga TNH was created in 1936, and Iran received about fifty tanks of this type. Based on this project CKD developed another tank Praga TNH-S intended for the Czechoslovak Army. After testing the prototype in 1937-38, the tank TNH-S entered service in August 1938 under the designation LT vz.38. Thus, CKD managed to beat its major competitor Skoda. A total of 10 LT vz.38(t) were produced by mid-March 1939. This vehicle was not only produced in Czechoslovakia but also by license in Sweden. The slightly re-designed Swedish tank was designated Strv m/41.
After Germany had occupied the Czech Republic, the LT vz.38 was almost immediately supplied to the German Army. The original vehicle was called L.T.M. 38 (Leichter Tank Muster 38, i.e. a light tank designed as of 1938) and it was only in 1940 that it received its designation Panzerkampfwagen 38 (t) abbreviated as Pz.Kpfw.38 (t). The German tanks did not differ from the LT vz.38 at first, except for the electric equipment and the German radio station installed there. The Pz.Kpfw.38 (t) was the only foreign tank not only supplied to the army but also produced in series after the occupation of the country. The tank production continued at CKD, which was renamed Bohmisch Mahriche Maschinenfabrik (BMM) after the occupation. A total of 475 tanks were produced from late May 1939 until November 1940 in four series (Ausf.A, Ausf.B, Ausf.C and Ausf.D). Each series had minor and sometimes hardly noticeable changes. For example, the tanks of the Ausf.C-D version had a thicker front armor plate (40 mm). In November 1940, the production of the Pz.Kpfw.38(t) Ausf.E tank began, which differed from its predecessors by a straight front armor plate and reinforced armor (with a hull and turret front of 50 mm and with hull and turret sides of 30 mm). The gross weight of this tank reached 9.87 tons, a large-size SPTA box was mounted on a shelf above the left track, and the suspension was reinforced. A total of 275 Pz.Kpfw.38(t) Ausf.E tanks were produced. Around 250 Pz.Kpfw.38(t) Ausf.F models were produced and it was almost identical with the previous model. The final major modification was the Pz.Kpfw.38(t) Ausf.G. BMM produced a total of 1,414 tanks of all modifications. A large number of various self-propelled artillery vehicles were produced on the basis of Pz.Kpfw.38(t). 
The fact that large-scale production of the LT vz.38 began after the Czech Republic had been occupied shows how much the Wehrmacht liked this tank. Upon creation this vehicle was the best light tank in the world, very closely related to the Pz.Kpfw.III Ausf.E in its features. This tank could not cope with the T-34 but they had different weight classes. The Pz.Kpfw.38(t) became obsolete by mid-1942.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/ger/pz_ib]
In 1935, a commander tank designated Kleiner Panzerbefehlswagen I A (also known as Sd.Kfz.265) was designed from the Pz.Kpfw.I Ausf.A. The turret was replaced with a superstructure which could hold two crew members (a commander and a radio operator) and two radio stations. Six such vehicles were produced in late 1935.
In 1936, an upgraded version of the tank was designed based on the Pz.Kpfw.I Ausf.B chassis. Apart from the new chassis the tank designated Kleiner Panzerbefehlswagen I B differed in its standard armament (one MG-34 7.92 mm machine gun) and a redesigned superstructure. Two series of the Kleiner Panzerbefehlswagen I B were produced with a total number of 200 vehicles. The tanks were upgraded before the Polish campaign of 1939 and received a FuG 8 radio station, the frame aerial being replaced by a stub antenna. 
Like most commander vehicles, the Kleiner Panzerbefehlswagen I B should not be treated as a front combat unit. Commander tanks were supposed to stay back and to coordinate the tank groups, while their own armament provided protection only against enemy infantry.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/ger/pz_iic]
In late 1934 the Army Ordnance Department ordered the development of a light tank weighing 10 tons and equipped with a 20 mm gun. Since the Treaty of Versailles prohibited Germany from developing and producing tanks, the project was designated La.S 100 (Landwirtschaftlicher Schlepper 100, i.e. an agricultural tractor 100). Four firms took part in the contest for the development of the La.S 100, and the joint design by MAN and Daimler-Benz was chosen.
The first ten tanks of this type were produced in late 1935. By that time they were designated Panzerkampfwagen II Ausfuehrung A (abbreviated as Pz.Kpfw.II Ausf.A) and the Wehrmacht’s official designation Sd.Kfz.121. Three series of the Pz.Kpfw.II Ausf.A were produced as well as a Pz.Kpfw.II Ausf.B version, which was slightly different from the others. The Pz.Kpfw.II Ausf.C, which had a different running gear, was produced in large numbers; a total of 1,113 Pz.Kpfw.II Ausf.C tanks were produced.
The Pz.Kpfw. II was primarily intended for training the crews. Nevertheless, the Pz.Kpfw.II was used by the troops until 1943 and unlike the smaller Pz.Kpfw.I it kept a fighting chance. When the Pz.Kpfw.II Ausf.C appeared it was already inferior in armamentto such tanks as the 7TP and T-26 designed as of 1933, but it could still fight against them. The German tank was several times more maneuverable, which was a decisive factor in more than one case.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/ger/pz_iif]
The 1939 campaign showed the need to upgrade the Pz.Kpfw.II Ausf.C, primarily to reinforce its armor. This resulted in a Pz.Kpfw.II Ausf.F tank. The new modification looked different with its sloped front hull, a hull-wide upper front armor plate and a commander’s cupola with a single-piece hatch. The improved armor protection added about half a ton of weight to the tank but with almost no impact on maneuverability. 
The first prototypes of the Pz.Kpfw.II Ausf.F were ready by June 1940, but its mass production began only in March next year. A total of 524 tanks of this version were produced.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/ger/pz_iiif]
In 1934 the Army Ordnance Department ordered the development of a medium tank. The order required that the tank should have a combat weight of 15 tons and its armament should consist of a 37 mm gun and three 7.92 mm machine guns. The project was entitled Zugfuhrerwagen, i.e. squad commander vehicle. This name was chosen to keep the project a secret: in fact the Zugfuhrerwagen was developed as the main tank of the Reichswehr (and later the Wehrmacht). According to the organizational chart, each tank battalion was to include three squads of “squad commander vehicles.” 
Four firms took part in the contest for the development, and the design by Daimler-Benzwas finally chosen. By that time the tank was designated Panzerkampfwagen III and received the  official Wehrmacht designation Sd.Kfz.141. In 1936, 10 Pz.Kpfw.III Ausf.A tanks were produced, which were essentially trial vehicles. Their running gear featured five road wheels on either side, each wheel with an individual helical spring. The next two series, Ausf.B and Ausf.C (12 and 15 tanks respectively) featured a new running gear with eight road wheels on each side. The road wheels had leaf springs. In 1938 a new modification, Ausf.D, appeared and 30 such vehicles were produced. The tank still had a complex and expensive leaf spring suspension but this vehicle could was considered to be pretty much fit for combat conditions. The reinforced armor brought the tank weight up to 19.8 tons.
The Pz.Kpfw.III Ausf.E was the first real mass production model of the Pz.Kpfw.III series. This vehicle featured a torsion bar suspension designed by Ferdinand Porsche. The tank also had a new engine, two-piece side hatches installed in the turret, and a re-designed ball mount for the bow machine gun. The hull sides now had escape hatches. A total of 96 Pz.Kpfw.III Ausf.E tanks were produced. In September 1939 the Pz.Kpfw.III Ausf.F version entered mass production. This tank differed from the previous versions in air intakes added to the front armor plate to cool the brakes. A total of 435 tanks of this version were produced. Around 100 tanks were equipped with the 50 mm Kw.K 38 L/42  gun mounted in a new mantlet (while one of the coaxial machine guns was removed at the same time). Later on, all the tanks of the Ausf.E-F versions were rearmed in the same way.
Due to the long search for the best running gear there were fewer Pz.Kpfw.III in the army than Pz.Kpfw.IV, which were support tanks, by September 1939. The Pz.Kpfw.III became the principal German tank in 1940 and retained this status until late 1942. The armor of the first Pz.Kpfw.III models could be penetrated by almost all the types of the enemy anti-tank guns; but at that time there was not a single medium tank with shell-proof armor. The Pz.Kpfw.III had a number of advantages compared to enemy tanks: e.g. a perfect optical system and comfortable crew compartment. The Pz.Kpfw.III crew was increased up to 5 people and allowed the tank commander to concentrate on his core duties. The battles in France clearly showed the weakness of the 37 mm Kw.K.35/36 L/46.5 gun, which was a tank version of the Pak 35/36 anti-tank cannon. The Pz.Kpfw.III concept envisaged the development of a combat vehicle primarily to fight against enemy tanks, but the French B1-bis tanks appeared to be too tough for it. The installation of a more powerful 50 Kw.K 38 L/42 gun resolved this problem to some extent, but the limits were again shown after the beginning of Operation Barbarossa when the Pz.Kpfw.III encountered the Soviet T-34 and KV-1 tanks.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/ger/pz_iiij]
In December 1941, the Pz.Kpfw.III Ausf.J model with a 50 mm Kw.K.39 L/60 gun entered production. Adolf Hitler himself insisted in the installation of a long-barrel 50 mm gun since mid-1940. Such persistence was quite understandable: the 50 mm Kw.K.38 L/42 gun, which started to be installed on the Pz.Kpfw.III from June 1940, despite having higher armor-piercing ability than the 37 mm gun, could only destroy heavy enemy tanks at close distances. The delay was mostly caused by problems in installing the gun; also, the rounds for the Kw.K.39 L/60 were larger than those for the short-barrel gun and the ammunition load decreased (from 99 to 84 rounds). A total of 1,067 Pz.Kpfw.III Ausf.J tanks armed with 50 mm Kw.K.39 L/60 guns were produced.
The installation of the new guns made it possible to even the odds of the Pz.Kpfw.III with the T-34 and KV-1 in combat. The Panzergrenade 40/1 armor-piercing round penetrated a 76 mm thick armored plate at 500 meters. Yet, the fire power was insufficient to give the German tank an advantage. Together with the fact that it was impossible to install a more powerful gun without serious re-design this resulted in closing the Pz.Kpfw.III production in favor of the StuG.40 Ausf.G.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/ger/pz_iiim]
The production of the Pz.Kpfw.III Ausf.M, the final modification of the Pz.Kpfw.III series, began in October 1942. The tank was a further development of the Pz.Kpfw.III Ausf.L and, like its predecessor, was equipped with additional spaced armor located in the hull front and the gun mantlet. The major difference of the Pz.Kpfw.III Ausf.M consisted in a new muffler, which increased maximum fording depth to 1.3 meters. Also, the escape hatches in the hull sides were removed, the smoke grenade dischargers were mounted on the turret sides and the spotlights changed their position a little. Since 1943, the tanks were equipped with side skirts decreasing the effect of hollow-charge rounds. 
Only 250 of the scheduled 1,000 tanks were produced in the original version. Another 100 Pz.Kpfw.II were built as Flammpanzer III (Pz.Kpfw.III (Fl)) flame-thrower tanks, and yet another 213 vehicles were completed as Pz.Kpfw.III Ausf.N close support tanks. Another 165 hulls were used to produce the StuG.40 Ausf.G assault guns.
By the time the Pz.Kpfw.III Ausf.M entered production it had actually ceased being the main tank of the Wehrmacht. It could still fight against the T-34 and KV-1, but at distances of only up to 500m. By that time the troops were supplied with the Pz.Kpfw.IV Ausf.G tanks with a far more powerful 75 mm Kw.K.L/48 gun.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/ger/pz_ivc]
In 1934, the Army Ordnance Department ordered the development of a medium tank designated as Zugfuhrerwagen (ZW), i.e. a platoon commander’s vehicle. This tank became known later under the designation Pz.Kpfw.III. Simultaneously, an order was issued to develop a support tank armed with a short-barrel 75 mm gun and weighing no more than 24 tons. This tank was designated as Bataillonsfuhrerwagen (BW), i.e. battalion commander’s vehicle. Just as with theZugfuhrerwagen, this was a deliberately misleading name: according to the organizational chart each tank battalion was to include one platoon of these tanks. The BW was a medium tank on paper, but it was classified as heavy tankby the Germans.
Three firms took part in the contest for the design of the Bataillonsfuhrerwagen, and finally Krupp’s design VK2001/K was chosen. Interesting enough is that this design was a redesigned version of the MKA tank which had participated in the contest for the development of the Zugfuhrerwagen. Krupp Co. had to considerably redesign the BW, in particular rebuild the running gear which finally consisted of eight dual road wheels per side. The road wheels were grouped into bogies suspended on leaf springs. Unlike the Pz.Kpfw.III, the road wheel suspension of the new tank proved successful and remained almost unchanged throughout its production period. 
The first BW prototypes were ready in 1936. By that time the vehicle was designated Panzerkampfwagen IV and received the official Wehrmacht designation Sd.Kfz.161. The Pz.Kpfw.IV Ausf.A was only a little heavier than the Pz.Kpfw.III Ausf.A. The first Pz.Kpfw.IV had quite modest armor (the maximum armor thickness being 20 mm) and only a total of 35 Pz.Kpfw.IV Ausf.A tanks were produced. In 1937, the production of an improved model, the Pz.Kpfw.IV Ausf.B, began. The tank was up-armored, yet for some unclear reasons the ball mount of the machine gun was removed (restored again on the Pz.Kpfw.IV Ausf.D). The front armor plate was straightened and a number of tanks received an improved commander’s cupola. A total of 45 Pz.Kpfw.IV Ausf.B were produced.
Since 1938, the first mass produced version of the Pz.Kpfw.IV entered production known as Pz.Kpfw.IV Ausf.C. It was a substantiallyimproved version of the Pz.Kpfw.IV Ausf.B. A new engine was installed in the tank. A total of 134 tanks of this model were produced.
By the beginning of the Polish Campaign the Pz.Kpfw.IV tanks outnumbered the Pz.Kpfw.III tanks, which they were supposed to support. The first Pz.Kpw.IV models had quite weak armor and their gun was better capable to destroy enemy infantry rather than tanks. The 75 mm Kw.K.37 L/24 gun was efficient against the lightly armored 7TP and English cruiser tanks, but it could inflict little damage on such vehicles as the Somua S-35 not to mention the B1 bis and the Matilda II. Fighting against tanks, however, was not the major task of the Pz.Kpfw.IV. In terms of design it was a more successful vehicle than the Pz.Kpfw.III, with large room for improvement.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/ger/pz_ivf2]
The battles on the Eastern Front in 1941 highlighted the insufficient firepower of the German tank guns. In December 1941, production of the Pz.Kpfw.III Ausf.J began, which was equipped with a long 50 mm gun, but its power was still insufficient to fight against the T-34 and the KV-1 at long distances. It was impossible to install a larger caliber gun on the Pz.Kpfw.III.
The 50 mm gun was planned to be installed on the Pz.Kpfw.IV, but finally it became clear that a more powerful cannon was needed. At last the 75 mm Kw.K 40 L/43 gun was chosen. The Pz.Kpfw.IV Ausf.F armed with this gun entered service in 1942 under the designation Pz.Kpfw.IV Ausf.F2. At the same time, the Pz.Kpfw.IV Ausf.F armed with a short-barrel gun was re-designated Pz.Kpfw.IV Ausf.F1. The production of the Pz.Kpfw.IV Ausf.F2 began in March 1942, with a total of 175 tanks produced and another 25 vehicles converted from the Pz.Kpfw.IV Ausf.F1.
The beginning of the Pz.Kpfw.IV Ausf.F2 mass production meant that the Wehrmacht had finally a tank capable of fighting against enemy vehicles at long distances. The Kw.K.40 L/75 armor-piercing round penetrated a 82-mm-thick plate at one kilometer. The appearance of the new cannon, however, had a negative effect, too, as the load on the front road wheels increased. This resulted in a shorter service life.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/ger/pz_ivh]
Mass production of the Pz.Kpfw.IV Ausf.H began in April 1943. A total of 3,374 tanks of this type were manufactured, the most of the entire Pz.Kpfw.IV family. Its armor was reinforced compared to the previous models and the front armor plate thickness reached 80 mm. The suspension was reinforced, too, helping with the increased load on the front road wheels. Like the later modifications of the Pz.Kpfw.IV Ausf.G, the Ausf.H tanks were equipped with 5-mm-thick skirts protecting against hollow-charge rounds. Zimmerit anti-magnetic paste was applied to protect the tanks against magnetic mines. The tanks were continuously re-designed during production: all-steel return rollers were added (due to the lack of rubber) and the road wheels and idlers were re-shaped. Production of the Pz.Kpfw.IV Ausf.H stopped in July 1944 and replaced by a simplified tank model, the Pz.Kpfw.IV Ausf.J.
The Pz.Kpfw.IV front armor was reinforced, making it immune to Soviet 76 mm tank guns. On the other hand, most of the shells would hit the turret, where the 50-mm-thick armor remained unchanged. Its weight increasing up to 26 tons, the tank became less maneuverable, which could be a serious drawback in a tank battle. Nevertheless, the Pz.Kpfw.IV Ausf.H was a difficult opponent capable of damaging enemy tanks from outside of the range of their guns.  

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/ger/pz_vg_(panther)]
The Panzerkampfwagen V Panther was a response to the Т-34. According to the German classification, the Pz.Kpfw.V was a medium tank although judging by its weight (over forty tons) and armor protection it was really a heavy tank. This confusion was due to the fact that Wehrmacht classification of tanks was based on the gun caliber rather than on tank weight. 
Development of the Pz.Kpfw.V started in 1941, with two companies, namely Daimler-Benz and MAN, participating in the contest. The tank designed by Daimler-Benz copied the T-34 in many aspects, including appearance and layout. MAN on the other hand developed a typical German-style design (with the engine in the rear and transmission and drive wheels in the front). The MAN prototype was finally chosen, was improved and put into mass production under the designation Pz.Kpfw.V Panther Ausf.D.
In March 1944, the production of the Pz.Kpfw.V Ausf.G, the most popular Panther model, began. The hull was re-designed, the driver’s hatch was removed from the front armor plate. The driver’s and radio operator’s hatches were hinged and re-shaped. The hull armor became thicker and the side armor plates were installed at sloped angles. The vehicles produced after November 1944 had a re-shaped gun mantlet, modified armor protection for the exhaust pipes (which incorporated flash suppressors as well), and a fan above the engine compartment.  A total of 2,953 Pz.Kpfw.V Ausf.G tanks were produced. From late 1944-1945, some tanks were equipped with the FG1250 infrared searchlights.
The Pz.Kpfw.V is considered to be one of the best German tanks during WWII and rightly so. Combining powerful armor and armament with pretty good maneuverability, the Panther was a menacing opponent indeed. It should not be implied that the Pz.Kpfw.V had no weaknesses. Its Achilles’ heel was the running gear, which provided for smooth movement but turned out to be the most unreliable part. The running gear accounted for almost half of all mechanical damages, with engine problems ranking second. This was mostly due to the tank’s excessive weight. According to the armor layout, the front plates were thickest (80 mm for the hull and 110 mm for the turret), while the sides were only 40 mm thick, which was thinner than the armor of the Т-34. Also, the quality of the German steel began to decrease sharply after mid-1944, which negatively affected armor protection. At the same time, the Pz.Kpfw.V had at least one unquestionable advantage over enemy tanks: the 75 mm Kw.K 42 L/70 gun, penetrating 89-mm of armor at two kilometers.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/ger/pz_vib_(tiger_ii)]
The Tiger II, or King Tiger, was a massive and menacing combat vehicle. Developed by Henschel specifically for absolute battlefield superiority it could only fulfill this task in the hands of an experienced crew. Of all the tanks built during WWII, this was the heaviest, best protected, and best-armored tank and would be formidable even by today’s standards. The price of such supremacy was its excessive size and weight and inferior mobility. The reliability of the engine and transmission decreased due to the high combat weight. This is not a big problem for static defense operations but is a monumental drawback in an offensive. The Tiger II was tested during the Ardennes Offensive carried out by the Germans and failed to make an impression.
Like its predecessor, the King Tiger had a welded hull. Based on the experienced with the Soviet T-34, the armor plates were installed at a steep angle. The hull of the Tiger II resembled the Panther. The turret was quite spacious in spite of the fact that the gun divided it into two parts and almost reached the rear wall. A total of 78 rounds were stacked along the turret walls and on the floor, with additional equipment located on numerous racks. The turret could be traversed 360 degrees in 19 to 77 seconds (compared to 17 seconds for the British Cromwell tank) depending on the main engine RPM since the engine also powered the turret drive. The turret could also be traversed manually by turning the gunner’s hand wheel 704 times or the loader’s hand wheel 680 times.
The commander had a perfect view from his cupola but usually preferred to sit up with his head poked out of the hatch when on the move. The powerful long-barrel 88 mm gun was superior to almost all Allied tank guns in terms of range and armor-piercing ability, allowing the Tiger II to frontally attack any targets. The rapid-firing gun had a problem with its barrel wearing out fast. Therefore, the later models were equipped with two-piece gun barrels.
The PzKpfw VI Tiger II tank was only made in one version, the Ausf.В. A total of 485 vehicles were produced. The King Tiger production was not interrupted even under most severe bombings. There were constantly at least 60 vehicles in production at Henschel’s factory. At its peak the production of one Tiger II would only require 15 days. The tank had minor improvements during the mass production run. These changes included the installation of an upgraded 88 mm KwK 43/III gun with a re-shaped mantlet and a number of minor improvements in the armor protection of the engine compartment. The prototype and some tanks of the first production series were equipped with the binocular TZF 9b sighting telescope while the tanks produced later on had the monocular TZF 9d/1 sighting telescope. In 1944, most of the Tigers fighting on the Western Front were supplied with armor protection for the air intake shutter for the engine compartment to protect the engine from air attacks. The tanks also differed from each other in the way accessories and spare parts were mounted on the shelves above the tracks. Since fall 1944, King Tigers were supplied to heavy tank battalions in small batches of 4 or 5. The Tigers II were hard to disguise due to their large size and would lag behind quickly during a mobile fight. But in the hands of an experienced crew the King Tiger was very dangerous and could attack enemy tanks by itself and destroy several of them without being damaged itself. On the Eastern Front, the Tiger II tanks were first used on August 13, 1944 during the attack on the village of Staszow (the Sandomierz bridgehead, Poland). The King Tigers of the 501st Heavy Tank Battalion got into an ambush arranged by the 53rd Armor Guards Brigade and their artillery support units (with a total of 200 barrels with calibers ranging from 57 to 152 mm). According to Soviet data, 24 Tigers were hit (11 according to the German data). Three tanks were captured in fully operational condition. Almost at the same time the PzKpfw VI Ausf. saw combat on the Western front: the 503rd Heavy Tank Battalion attacked the Shermans of the 148th Royal Tank Regiment.
Aviation became the major force to counter King Tigers on the Western Front.   The 503rd Battalion was bombed by 2,100 Allied airplanes on July 18, 1944.
As of March 1, 1945 there were 226 PzKpfw VI Tiger II Ausf. В tanks in combat service.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/ger/pz_vie_(tiger_i)]
Unlike the armies of other states, the Wehrmacht did not have proper heavy tanks at the beginning of the war. Formally, its heavy tank was the Pz.Kpfw.IV, but in fact this vehicle was better rated as medium tank. This doesn’t mean that the Germans hadn’t worked at designing heavy tanks. In 1932, Rheinmetall developed a heavy multi-turret tank NeubauFahrzeug (NbZf) and a total of 5 such vehicles were manufactured. This tank was not a proper combat vehicle and it was not developed any further. A totally different vehicle was required with proper armor protection and more elaborate design.
The development of such a tank began in 1937 when the company Henschel was engaged to create a breakthrough tank, the Durchbruchwagen (DW), with a combat weight of 30 tons. The tank was to have a turret and armament similar to the Pz.Kpfw.IV. Two prototypes were made. The DW was followed by a prototype VK3001, when Ferdinand Porsche joined the competition for the creation of a heavy tank. The design proposed by the company Porsche and designated VK3001(P) became a prototype for the Typ 100 Leopard heavy tank. In the designers’ opinion the tank was to have either a 75 mm gun similar to the one installed on the Pz.Kpfw.IV or a 105 mm howitzer. The zest of the VK3001(P) was the electromechanical transmission, Ferdinand Porsche’s favorite brainchild. In March 1941, two prototypes of the VK3001(H) were ready almost at the same time with prototypes of the VK3001(P). In May 1941, the concept changed again and both designs of the VK3001 were rejected. Yet, the vehicles designed by Henschel found their application as they were used as a basis for developing two samples of a heavy tank destroyer: the 12.8 cm Selbstfahrlafette L/61 (Panzerselbstfahrlafette V) also known under the name of Sturer Emil. These vehicles took part in operations on the Eastern Front and one of them was captured by Soviet troops near Stalingrad in late 1942.
Porsche’s new vehicle, the VK4501(P), was developed with a 88 mm gun to be installed in Krupp’s turret. At the same time, Henschel created another prototype VK3601(H), which was to be armed with a promising 75 mm gun with a conic barrel. Tests showed that the gun would remain an experiment, so the VK3601(H) was quickly re-designed to accommodate a turret similar to the one designed for the VK4501(P). This vehicle was designated VK4501(H). In April and May 1942, the competing companies’ vehicles participated in comparative testing. Henschel’s tank proved to be better than Porsche’s brainchild: the VK4501(H) was more maneuverable, consumed less fuel and above all was less complicated in its design than the VK4501(P). By that time both companies had been actively producing units and hulls for new tanks, which resulted in a curious situation when Porsche, which had lost the contest, managed to produce 90 chasses of the VK4501(P).
In summer 1942, the VK4501(H) entered service under the designation Panzerkampfwagen VI Ausf.H1 Tiger and receive the official Wehrmacht designation Sd.Kfz.181. After the production of the Pz.Kpfw.VI Ausf.B Tiger II, the tank was designated Pz.Kpfw.VI Ausf.E Tiger I. A total of 1,350 were produced from August 1942 through August 1944. The tank was constantly improved and four basic series can be identified. The tanks of the first series produced between August and December 1942 differed quite substantially from each other particularly in their differently shaped stowage bins added to the rear turrets. The next series produced from January through June 1943 featured a turret escape hatch which replaced the pistol port in the turret’s right side. The tanks produced in winter 1943, like the vehicles of the first series, had non-standard rear-turret stowage bins. A more powerful engine was introduced starting from the 251st vehicle; also, the first Tiger Ausf.H1 tanks had underwater driving equipment enabling them to cross 4.5-meter-deep waterways. Since May 1943, the tanks were armed with 100 mm dischargers to fight back enemy infantry attacks. Up until August 1943, the vehicles were equipped with air filters. The so-called medium series, the Tiger Ausf.H1, appeared in July-August 1943. The tanks of this series featured commander’s cupolas similar to those used on the Pz.Kpfw.V A and a standardized way of fastening spare tracks on the turret. There was also a ring in the commander’s cupola for mounting the 7.92 mm MG-34 machine gun. During the production the dischargers were removed from the turret and the hull and replaced by the Nahverteidigungswaffe grenade launchers mounted on top of the turret. Since January 1944, the so-called late series of the tank entered production. The vehicles of this series are easy to be distinguished due to their road wheels with inner shock absorption; they also featured reinforced turret armor (the top was 45 mm thick) and other minor changes.
The Pz.Kpfw.VI Ausf.H1 is undoubtedly the best heavy tank of WWII. The appearance of this vehicle meant that absolutely all existing tanks had immediately become obsolete. Its powerful armor reaching 100 mm in its front made the Tiger invulnerable for enemy tank guns (the hull sides remained vulnerable), while the armor-piercing round of its 88 mm Kw.K.36 L/56 gun installed on the Pz.Kpfw.VI Ausf.H1 penetrated 84-mm of armor plate at two kilometers. The Tiger was fairly mobile, which would partially offset the slow turret rotation. It was by spring 1944, when the production of the Tiger tanks was coming to an end, that they got a decent rival – the IS-2. It is noteworthy that although the Pz.Kpfw.VI Ausf.H1 had had no match among enemy tanks before that time, the first self-propelled guns capable of fighting against the Tiger appeared already by mid-1943, namely the SU-122 and the SU-152. One may say that Henschel’s designers managed to find the most perfect formula for a heavy tank, although the German designers increased the weight later on, which affected their mobility and reliability. Weight problems were already apparentwith the Tiger: e.g. its least reliable parts were the rubber cushions of the road wheels.  Also, the Tiger was far from a small tank, yet the Pz.Kpfw.V Panther, classified as a medium tank, was even bigger. Anyway, the Pz.Kpfw.VI Ausf.H1 remained a very dangerous rival for all the types of Soviet, American, and British tanks up to the end of the war.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/pol/7tp]
In early 1930s Poland imported 38 Vickers 6-Ton tanks from the UK. The tank’s easily inflammable engine was replaced by an Austrian-made Diesel Saurer. Along with replacing the engine, the tank’s armor protection was reinforced. The armament of the 7ТР included a 37 mm antitank Bofors gun and coaxial 7.92 mm Browning machine gun protected by an armored tube.
In two years about 90 vehicles of this type were manufactured.
In 1938 the tank was improved and the turret was enlarged with a rear compartment that housed a radio and extra ammunition load. The vehicle was equipped with a new device, a semi-gyrocompass that enabled movement in low visibility conditions.
By September 1, 1939 about 152 7TP and similar Vickers 6-Ton tanks were in service in Polish Army. Supported by infantry and artillery those vehicles managed to destroy about 200 German tanks of a total of 2,800 which took part in the Polish campaign.  
Also, the artillery tractor С7Р developed on the base of the 7TP was put into serial production.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/pol/tks]
The British Caden-Loyd MKVI tankette served as the prototype for design of the TK Tankette. In 1929 a department of the Polish Defense Ministry purchased 10 such tankettes from the British company Vickers-Armstrong. 
In 1930, a group of Polish engineers designed and built two models of a high-speed recon tank (TK-1 and TK-2) armed with a 7.92 mm machine gun. But the tankette was not put into serial production because of the lack of armor protection.
Later Polish engineers designed an improved version, the TK-3. In 1931 the first vehicle was assembled at the Ursus plant and soon serial production of the TK-3 began. By the end of 1933 about 300 TK-3 tankettes were produced.
In March 1933 work on a new recon tank was concluded. It was issued to Polish army units as TKS.  The new tankette had a new design and better armor protection.
The TKS Tankette was modified several times during development and production. Before the outbreak of World War II the TKS and TK-3 were rearmed with a 20 mm automatic gun. Also, a series of experiments was conducted with the goal to improve armor protection, replace the power unit and armament. As result dozens of new vehicles based on the TK-3 and the TKS were developed: the TKD with 47 mm gun, the TKW with rotating turret, the TKF with a more powerful engine and better armor protection.
More than 400 TK-3 tankettes and about 260 TKS tankettes were engaged in combat in September 1939. The tankettes were used in special reconnaissance tank companies that were part of infantry divisions. Thin armor and weak armament made these tankettes no rivals to the German Pz. II, Pz. III and Pz. IV tanks.

