[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/pol/vickers_e_dw]
In the late 1920s the Polish Army needed a modern home produced tank. Since Poland lacked experience in tank engineering, the decision was made to purchase abroad a license for manufacturing. As a resultthe Vickers Mk.E and 7TP light tanks entered service in the Polish Army.
In 1928 Vickers Armstrong Limited built the first prototype of the 6-ton Light Tank Mark E.  The tank was designed in two versions: the Mk.E – dual-turret, armed with machine guns; and the Mk. E type, the world’s first tank with twin armament, a gun and a machine gun in a single turret (duplex mounting).
The first 6-ton tank passed trials in Poland in September 1930 and in September 1931 the decision was made to purchase 50 machines and license the tank for local production. But Poland never started to manufacture the Vickers E Tank, because Polish designers improved its design and developed a new light tank, the 7TP. The tanks ordered were modified in 1934 and in August of the same year they officially entered the ranks of the Polish Army.
After the Vickers E entered service, a special 3rd Armored Battalion headquartered in Warsaw was created equipped with these tanks. In the late 1930s when the 7TP first entered service, the Vickers tanks were moved to the 2nd Battalion in Zurawica.  Another tank unit equipped with Vickers tanks was the 11th Battalion of the Armored Forces Training Center in Modlin. About 5 tanks in each battalion served as ‘immediate reserve’ and were never used in peacetime. The remaining tanks were actively used for training purposes and hence most of them were heavily worn-out by 1939.

