[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/rus/bt_7_mod_1935]
In 1934, an improved version of the wheel-track tank BT-5 was being developed. The new vehicle retained the turret of its predecessor’s (identical to the T-26 tank produced between 1934 and 1937) as well as armament but the hull design saw multiple changes. The hull front was welded unlike the BT-2 and BT-5 and the hull was up-armored. An M-17T engine was installed, which was the tank version of the M-17 aviation engine. Due to the installation of the new engine the exhaust pipes were modified, too; the same pipes appeared on the upgraded BT-5 tanks as well.
The first prototype of the new tank was produced in 1934 and mass production of the vehicle designated BT-7 began at the beginning of the following year. An upgraded version of the tank with a conic turret entered production in 1937, and a small-link track was added in 1938. In December 1930, the production of the final version of the BT-7 began, mainly known under the designation BT-7M (the tank was also designated BT-8). Unlike the previous BT version it was equipped with a V-2 diesel engine and 22-mm-thick reinforced frontal armor, yet its only visible difference was the air filter cap on the engine plate. A total of 5,328 tanks of the BT-7 family were produced including 155 BT-7A and 788 BT-7M tanks.
Like all wheel-track tanks, the main advantage of the BT-7 was its high speed. The BT-7 had a maximum road speed of 72 km/h (with tracks removed). The 45 mm gun was efficient against most enemy tanks. A major disadvantage of the BT-7 was its weak armor protection. It was this weak armor protection and the impossibility to strengthen it without major re-designs that led to a completely new design, the wheel-track tank BT-20, which evolved into the Т-34 later on.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/rus/bt_7a]
The BT-7 was also used as a basis for the creation of an artillery support tank known under the designation BT-7A. It differed from the basic model due to a new turret with the short-barrel 76 mm KT-28 gun (the same gun was installed on the early versions of the T-28).  The hull was also slightly modified to accommodate the new turret. A total of 155 BT-7A tanks were produced from 1937 through 1938 and 134 of them were supplied to the army.
The BT-7A had the same strengths and weaknesses as the basic model.   The KT-28 gun was quite efficient against enemy infantry, but the armor protection was definitely insufficient for a support tank. This was probably the reason for the small number of the BT-7A manufactured.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/rus/is_2]
In early 1942, the design bureau of the Kirov Factory in Chelyabinsk (ChKZ) started developing a tank designated KV-13. In fact, this was a brand-new vehicle which had next to nothing from its predecessor, the KV-1. Moreover, this tank was to be classified as a medium rather than heavy tank in terms of weight. Weighing 30 tons, the KV-13 was to have 75-mm-thick armor, a crew of 3, and armament consisting of the 76 mm ZIS-5 gun and the 7.62 mm DT coaxial machine gun. The vehicle seemed to be quite simple in production, which was important in a situation when tanks were needed badly. Unfortunately, the KV-13 prototype produced in spring 1942 proved extremely unreliable. Further tests were delayed as was the production of the second prototype with an up-armored hull (this brought the vehicle’s weight up to 38 tons). 
In January 1943 two samples of the German Pz.Kpfw.VI Ausf.H1 Tiger heavy tank were captured. Shooting tests carried out in April that year showed that the 76 mm F-34 and ZIS-5 tank guns could only penetrate the German vehicle’s armor at point-blank range (at a distance of up to 100-200 meters). The best-suited gun for destroying the Tiger was the 85 mm 52-K anti-aircraft cannon and the 122 mm A-19 howitzer. Neither gun would fit into the turrets of the tanks which were in serviceat the time, so new designs were needed. One of them was the KV-13 design which was renamed to IS (for Iosef Stalin) on February 24, 1943. In spring of 1943, two samples of the IS tank were produced: the IS-1 with a three-man turret and a 76 mm F-34M gun and the IS-2 with the 122 mm U-11 howitzer installed in the turret of the KV-9 tank prototype. In summer 1943, testing of the IS prototype armed with the 85 mm D-5T gun began. In September, this vehicle entered service under the designation IS-85. 
Meanwhile, in fall 1943, the 122 mm D-25T gun was developed consisting of a barrel from the 122 mm A-19 howitzer combined with the gun-cradle and the recoil mechanism of the U-11 howitzer. To decrease recoil, the barrel was equipped with a muzzle brake (during the production run the shape of the muzzle brake was changed several times). The tank armed with the D-25T gun successfully passed all tests and entered service under the designation IS-122. In March 1944, the IS-85 was re-designated IS-1 whereas the IS-122 was re-designated IS-2. During the production run the IS-2 design underwent a number of changes, the biggest of which was the remodeling of the hull front plate. A total of 3,483 tanks of this type were produced.
The IS-2 was undoubtedly the best Soviet heavy tank of WWII. But it is not quite appropriate to classify it as a heavy tank: weighing 46 tons it was only about a ton heavier than the Pz.Kpfw.V Panther referred to by the Germans as medium tank. The Pz.Kpfw.VI Ausf.H1 Tiger was 10 tons heavier than the IS-2, but the Soviet tank had better armor protection. Along with its advantages the IS-2 had its disadvantages, too, mainly regarding the low rate of fire of the D-25T gun (only 2-3 rounds per minute) and the poor quality of the driver sight. In theory, the armor-piercing round fired from the D-25T gun penetrated a 115-mm-thick plate, but tests quicklyshowed that this had been somewhat overestimated. Luckily as of summer 1944 the quality of German armor began to decrease sharply. The tanks of the early production series had weaker hull front armor, but this problem was solved in the summer of 1944, when production of hulls with the flattened front armor plate began.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/rus/kv_1]
In spring 1938, the Kirov Factory in Leningrad (LKZ) was ordered to develop a second-generation heavy multi-turret tank, which was to replace the Т-35. During the design process it became clear that the given specifications (weight of 60 tons and armor thickness of 60 mm) would only allow for a dual-turret design. Two prototypes (SMK and T-100) were built, which were combat-tested during the Russo-Finnish War of 1939-40. Both prototypes never made it past the experimental stage.
Along with the dual-turret tanks a single-turret variant was developed, which was designated KV (for Klim Voroshilov). Taking the SMK design as a basis, the designers considerably decreased the size of the hull and improved armor protection. The prototype KV-1, U-0, was armed with two guns: a 45 mm gun (the 1934 version) and a 76 mm L-11 gun. During tests which began in September 1939, the 45 mm gun was removed and replaced by a DT machine gun. In this version the U-0 was combat-tested during the Russo-Finnish War of 1939-40. In February 1940, the first vehicle of the pilot batch (U-2) was sent for combat testing. 
The KV tanks of the pilot batch featured rounded welded turrets.  The mass production tanks received an easier-to-produce cut welded turret. Before December 1940, the KV tanks were armed with 76 mm L-11 guns and a total of 142 tanks with such gun were manufactured. From January 1941 on, KV tanks (which were re-designated KV-1) were armed with 76 mm F-32 guns with better ballistic parameters. It was this version with the F-32 gun that became the most numerous modification of the KV-1 by the beginning of the Great Patriotic War. A total of 423 tanks were produced by July 1, 1941 by LKZ and also the Tractor Factory in Chelyabinsk (ChTZ). Since fall 1941, the KV-1 received a 76 mm ZIS-5gun. In January 1942, due to a lack of sheet steel, production of KV-1 tanks with cast turrets began alongside with welded turrets.
Before the Pz.Kpfw.VI Ausf.E Tiger appeared, the KV-1 had been the best heavy tank in the world. Unlike other heavy tanks of that time, the KV-1 had not only perfect armor protection but also armament fit for both fighting enemy infantry as well as armored vehicles. Unfortunately the reliability of the tank, particularly its running gear, was subpar. Technical faults accounted for a considerable part of KV-1 losses. These were also contributed to a lack of trained crews. Yet, when properly handled, the KV-1 was a menacing weapon which could only be rivaled by the following German weapons in 1941: the 88 mm Flak 18/36 anti-aircraft gun and the 50 mm Pak 38 anti-tank gun.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/rus/kv_2]
In late 1939, an assault tank based on the KV was designed, armed with a 152 mm M-10 howitzer (the 1938 version). Besidesthe armament the new vehicle differed in its larger turret designated MT-1. The tank was primarily designed to destroy enemy fortifications. The first tank to receive the MT-1 turret was the U-0 tank (the KV prototype) after its return from combat testing. In February three vehicles (U-0, U-1 and U-3) were sent for combat testing and participated in breaking through the Mannerheim Line. The first samples had a special muzzle brake, but it was frequently torn off during the tests and rejected. 
Mass production of the tank initially designated “big turret KV” began in early spring 1940. The first 46 tanks were equipped with MT-1 turrets. In fall of that year an improved variant of the tank was designed with a lowered turret and this version became the main model of this series. A total of 167 tanks with a lowered turret were produced until July 1941 (in 1941 they were designated KV-2). 
As mentioned above, the KV-2 was intended to destroy the enemy fortifications, primarily pillboxes. In a situation when the Soviet tanks had to defend rather than attack, there was no longer any need for the KV-2 tanks and their production stopped. This should not imply, however, that the KV-2 was a bad tank; it suffices to say that after point-blank hits of the 152 mm shell, enemy tanks would literally crumble with their welded seams breaking apart. Just like with the KV-1, the major weakness of the KV-2 was its unreliability, especially its running gear.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/rus/t_26_mod_1933]
Just like several other countries, the USSR became interested in the Vickers Mk.E tank developed by the British company Vickers-Armstrongs Ltd. in 1928. In spring 1930, the Soviet delegation signed a contract for the supply of 15 Vickers Mk.E Type A tanks, including the designs for its mass production. Initially designated V-26 the tank was supplied to the Red Army in spring 1931 under the designation T-26 (the 1931 version). A total of 1,626 tanks of this type were manufactured in 1931-33. Some of the tanks were equipped with a 37 mm Hotchkiss gun installed in the right turret. 
Along with expanding mass production of the T-26 (the 1931 version), the design bureau headed by S.A. Ginsburg started the development of a single-turret version. Unlike Poland, which purchased the sets for upgrading their tanks to the Vickers Mk.E Type B standard, the Soviet designers developed the turret on their own. A 45 mm 20-K gun (the 1932 version) and a 7.62 mm DT coaxial machine gun were installed into the two-man cylindrical turret. This vehicle entered service under the designation “T-26, 1933 Version.” The first vehicles were manufactured in the summer of 1933. The tank was continuously improved during production: since 1936 the hulls were welded and a ball mount with a DT machine gun was installed in the rear. Part of the vehicles produced in 1937 had an anti-aircraft ring mount with a DT machine gun. Some tanks were equipped with radio stations and they could be identified by a stub antenna on top of the turret. Since 1938, the “T-26, 1938 Version” with a conic turret entered mass production. The final version of the tank was the “T-26, 1939 Version” with a re-shaped hull. A total of 10,117 tanks of the T-26 family were produced from 1931 until 1940.
The T-26 created in mid-1930s had become obsolete by June 1941. The slow and poorly armored T-26 was quite an easy target for German anti-tank guns. Yet, in a fight against enemy tanks (especially light tanks) the T-26 had a fair chance: its 45 mm gun round could penetrate the armor of most German tanks at the time.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/rus/t_27]
In spring 1930, a Soviet delegation visited Great Britain and signed a contract with Vickers-Armstrongs Ltd. for the purchase of four types of armored vehicles. These included the Vickers Carden-Loyd Mk.IV tankette, which undoubtedly was a groundbreaking vehicle for its class. Along with the tankettes, the designs needed for their mass production were purchased. The Vickers Carden-Loyd Mk.IV was used as a basis for the development of the Soviet version of the tankette featuring a more powerful engine and armor protection, as well as armament consisting of a 7.62 mm DT machine gun. In February 1931, the tankette entered service under the designation T-27. A total of 3,297 tankettes were supplied to the troops between 1931 and 1934. 
By late 1930s, tankettes had become obsolete. The T-27 was noexception, being mostly used for training purposes. In 1941, the T-27 tankettes also served as towing vehicles for 45 mm anti-tank guns in addition to their traditional roles (reconnaissance and infantry support in some cases)

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/rus/t_34_85]
The first attempts to create a more powerful gun for the T-34 tank were made as early as 1942 but the real efforts began only in early 1943. The results of shooting tests carried out with the Pz.Kpfw.VI Ausf.H1 Tiger captured in early 1943 showed that the 85 mm 52-K anti-aircraft gun (the 1939 version) proved to be the most efficient. Almost at the same time, development of the 85 mm D-5T tank gun began, which was primarily intended for the KV-85. The tests showed that the standard turret of the T-34 was not suitable to accommodate the D-5T. It is noteworthy that Factory No. 112 was simultaneously developing a new turret with a support ring of 1,600 mm in diameter. This turret resembled the prototype of the T-43 in many respects. Tanks with the D-5T gun and a turret produced by Factory No. 112 are frequently called the “T-34/85, 1943 Version.” The tank produced by Factory No. 112 differed from the more numerous T-34/85 version in having a two-man turret. A total of 250-300 tanks of this type were produced.
On January 1, 1944, the 85 mm S-53 gun entered service with a simpler design than the D-5T. The gun was installed into a three-man turret produced by Factory No. 183. This tank entered service under the designation T-34/85 and its full-scale production began in March 1944. It should be mentioned that Factory No. 112 started to manufacture the Т-34/85 with new turrets but with D-5T guns in February that year. Tanks armed with the 85 mm S-53 gun had characteristic bulges along the gun mantlet sides. Since late October 1944, the Т-34/83 tanks were equipped with an upgraded version of the gun known under the designation ZIS-S-53. The gun mantlets of the tanks with ZIS-S-53 lost the bulges characteristic of the S-53. A total of 23,000 Т-34/85 tanks were produced in 1944-45.
Thanks to its new gun the Т-34/85 could take up a fight with the latest Pz.Kpfw.IV tanks, which were the main battle tank of the Wehrmacht since 1943. The turret provided a bit (although not much more) more space, which somewhat improved working conditions for the crew. At the same time, the armor protection remained unchanged along with a number of other weaknesses.  For example, the hull front armor plate was weakened because of the driver’s hatch and the installation of a bow machine gun. Also, continuous up-armoring of enemy tanks made it obvious that the power of the 85 mm ZIS-S-53 gun would not suffice for long. However, all these weaknesses did not prevent the Т-34/85 not only from becoming the most numerous medium tank during the final period of WWII but also from remaining in service for many decades thereafter (these tanks are still in service in some countries). 

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/rus/t_34_mod_1941]
In October 1937, Factory No. 183 (called the Kharkov Tractor Factory or KhTZ before 1936) was tasked with the development of a wheel-track tank which was to replace the BT-7 series. Upgrade the BT-7 hull was pointless; therefore, the tank with the factory designation BT-20 was designed from scratch borrowing only on the general layout and suspension of its predecessor. The prototype designated A-20 was produced in May 1939. Parallel to that, two prototypes designated A-32 were built on behalf of Mikhail Ilyich Koshkin, the chief designer of Factory No. 183, which represented a pure track version of the A-20. The two tanks featured different armament: the A-20 had a 45 mm gun (1938 version), whereas the A-32 had a 76 mm L-10 gun. The high maneuverability of the A-32 proved Koshkin right and the acceptance committee approved the development of the new version of the tank with increased armor (by 10 mm). 
The first two prototypes of the upgraded version of the A-32 designated A-34 were produced in January-February 1940. Koshkin died in September 1940, just at the time when his brainchild entered service under the designation T-34. Like the A-34, the new vehicle was armed with a 76 mm L-11 gun, which was the first timew that such a gun was installed on a medium tank. T-34 tanks were to be produced at two factories (Factory No. 183 and the Stalingrad Tractor Factory or STZ) but the production process took a long time to implement at STZ, so the tanks were mainly produced in Kharkov (117 vehicles in 1940). There were about four hundred T-34 tanks with the L-11 gun produced by March 1941, which are generally known under the designation “T-34, 1940 Version.” 
Since March 1941, production of the T-34 began with the 76 mm F-34 gun. This was the basic T-34 model when Germany attacked the USSR. A total of 1,225 tanks had been produced by July 1, 1941, STZ accounting for 294 of them and Factory No. 183 accounting for the other 931. Production of the T-34 tanks continued at Factory No. 183 through October with a total of 755 tanks produced. 
When the T-34 appeared, it was the best tank in its class. Because of its sloped armor plates the hull of the T-34 offered good protection against anti-tank shells while its powerful gun was able to kill enemy tanks at any distance. But it also had a number of weaknesses. The turret, which had only seen few changes from the time of the A-20, was cramped and could only house two crew members. Thus, in addition to his direct duties, the commander had to work as a loader. The turret offered restricted visibility and the front armor plate was weakened by the driver’s hatch(this weakness was only removed on the T-44). On top of that, the service life of the tank engine was only 150 hours. In spite of all its weaknesses the T-34 had a major strength: it was capable of fighting enemy tanks outside of the range of enemy shells. 

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/rus/t_34_mod_1943]
Starting in summer and fall 1942, several factories began to produce T-34 tanks with an “improved turret” developed by designer Nabutovsky. Its production technology was more efficient although the turret itself remained as cramped as the previous model. Tanks with this turret are known under the designation “T-34, 1942 Version” although they were manufactured in this configuration in 1943 as well.
In spring 1943, the T-34 produced by Factory No. 183 received a commander’s cupola. It’s noteworthy that the commander’s cupola already appeared on the A-43 (T-34M) tanks as early as in summer 1941, but the work was halted when war broke out. The tanks manufactured by Factory No. 183 also received additional fuel tanks, and some changes to the hull were introduced. In this configuration the tank is known as “T-34, 1943 Version”, although this designation is not quite correct. With some minor changes Factory No. 183 was producing this version up to spring 1944. There is no information as to the exact number of T-34 tanks with commander cupolas produced by Factory No. 183; one can only say that the factory manufactured 7,766 and 1,838 tanks in 1943 and 1944, respectively. The total number of T-34 tanks produced by all the factories in 1943 was 15,833.
The “T-34, 1943 Version” appeared at a time when German troops started receiving the Pz.Kpfw.IV Ausf.H, Pz.Kpfw.V Panther Ausf.D and Pz.Kpfw.IV Ausf.H1 Tiger tanks. These tanks enjoyed better armor protection and more powerful guns than the T-34. The 76 mm shells fired from the F-34 guns were efficient against the new enemy tanks only at a distance o up to half a kilometer, while a point-blank shot was needed to destroy the Pz.Kpfw.VI Ausf.H1. In short, the tank (especially its armament) soon required a serious upgrade.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/rus/t_40s]
In late 1938, development of a small-sized amphibious tank began with the goal to replace the T-38. The prototype designated “0-10” was fundamentally different from the earlier amphibious tanks. The tank had a high trapezoid hull in its cross-section, individual torsion bar suspension, and a conic tower with a 12.7 mm DShK machine gun and a 7.62 mm DT machine gun. The re-designed version “0-10” entered service in 1939 under the designation T-40 with a total of 374 tanks produced. 
Due to the urgent need for armored vehicles in summer 1940, a simplified version of the T-40 entered production which lacked the screw propeller in the rear. Such tanks are known under the designation T-40S, i.e. the land version. The rear compartment was removed in August 1941 and in the following month some of the vehicles were being armed with 20 mm TNSh (ShVAK) guns. Such vehicles are known under the designation T-30. 
Designed as a reconnaissance tank, the T-40 was the best tank in the world in its class when it appeared. Unfortunately, due to a general lack of armored vehicles this vehicle was often used as a line tank, which was an unusual role for it.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/rus/t_60]
In summer 1941, the Red Army lost a huge number of armored vehicles including T-26 light tanks. They were to be replaced by T-50 light tanks with an armor protection comparable to that of the T-34. But the T-50 never entered serial production. When the quickly decreasing fleet of T-26 tanks necessitated more light tanks, preferably easy to produce, this role was filled by a tank developed in August 1941 by a group of designers headed by N.A. Astrov. The design process was completed within a little more than two weeks. This record time was possible because the tank designated “0-60” was designed based on the T-40. Compared to its predecessor, the new tank’s hull and turret were completely re-designed, the armor protection was considerably improved, and the 20 mm TNSh gun (the “land” version of the ShVAK aerial gun) and the 7.62 mm DT machine gun were installed. In September 1941, the first tanks of the series designated T-60 began to be supplied to the troops. A total of 5,915 tanks of this type were produced. During the production run the design of the tank was continuously improved: e.g. in October 1941 its armor protection was increased bringing the T-60 weight up to 6,400 kg. 
In spite of the short design period, the T-60 turned out to be a good vehicle. It was comparable to the Pz.Kpfw.II Ausf.C/F, but since it was only efficient against light-armored enemy vehicles, the appearance of a more advanced T-70 tank was only a matter of time. 

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/rus/t_70m]
Almost immediately after the T-60 light tank entered mass production, the design bureau of the Gorky Automobile Factory headed by N.A. Astrov started to work on its successor. Taking the T-60 as a basis, the designers developed a better protected tank with far more powerful armament, consisting of a 45 mm gun (1938 version) and a DT coaxial machine gun. It was also equipped with a new power unit consisting of twin 6-cylinder engines. In January 1942, the tank entered service under the designation T-70 and its mass production began in March. The first vehicles had cast turrets which were quickly replaced by welded models. In September 1942, mass production of an improved version of the T-70 began, better known under the designation T-70M. Compared to the T-70, the running gear was reinforced (in particular a wider track was introduced) and a re-designed driver’s hatch was installed. A total of 8,226 tanks of both modifications were produced, making the T-70 second in terms of production volume of all Soviet tanks. Several self-propelled guns were designed based on the T-70, the most famous being the SU-76 (SU-12 and SU-15).
The T-70 was primarily intended to support infantry but unlike the T-60 this tank was a more dangerous opponent. While the T-70 was not able to penetrate most German tanks from the front with its 45 mm gun, there were instances when T-70 tanks managed to disable Pz.Kpfw.V Panthers with side shots. Like other design created within a short period of time, the T-70 had its weaknesseds, but it was nevertheless quite successful in its main role.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/uk/a12_(matilda_ii)]
In 1936, Vickers-Armstrong started development of the first British infantry tank with strong armor. The designers had a limit on the overall cost of the tank (not more than 6 thousand pounds sterling), which is why the resulting vehicle was quite special. Along with the powerful armor protection (armor thickness at the front reached 60 mm) the armament carried by this tank consisted of just one machine gun. The tank with the official name of Tank, Infantry, Mk.I Matilda and the designation A11 was known for its small size and its “brutal” look. Because the Tank, Infantry, Mk.I was designed to support infantry, its speed was moderate at 13 km/h.
The War Office realized that the firepower of the Tank, Infantry, Mk.I was insufficient. Attempts were made to install a two-man turret on the tank but the vehicle was simply too small inside. Development of an absolutely new tank started. The project was based on the design of the A7 medium tank model of 1931-36 which never saw serial production due to its low reliability. The creation of a new vehicle with the designation A12 and the name Matilda Senior began at the end of 1936 by the Vulcan Foundry Co. The tank borrowed the running gear and twin-engine power plant from the A7. The hull was redesigned from scratch (its narrow front was similar to that of the Tank, Infantry, Mk.I). Also, a two-seat turret was developed which carried a 40 mm ROFQ Mk.IX gun and a 7.7 mm Vickers coaxial machine gun.
The first prototype was named Tank, Infantry, Mk.II Matilda II and was manufactured in April 1938. In total some 2,987 tanks of this type were produced. The following variants of the Tank, Infantry, Mk.II were in production:

- Matilda II. Original production model with AEC twin-engines, 2 x 87 hp and armed with a 40 mm ROQF Mk.IX gun and a coaxial Vickers machine-gun;
- Matilda IIA. With Vickers MG replaced by a 7.92 mm BESA machine gun;
- Matilda III. With Leyland E148/E149 twin engine, 2 x 95 hp;
- Matilda III CS. With 76.2 mm OQF Mk.I howitzer instead of the 40 mm ROQF Mk.IX gun;
- Matilda IV. With a low commander turret and Leyland E1 E164/E165 twin engines, 2 x 95 hp;
- Matilda IV CS. With 76.2 mm OQF Mk.I howitzer instead of the 40 mm ROQF Mk.IX gun;
-	Matilda V. With improved gear box and gear shift pneumatic amplifier.

By September 1, 1939 only two Tank, Infantry, Mk.II Matilda II units were in service. These tanks first saw action in the British counterattack near Arras: the total number of tanks engaged in combat included 58 tanks Mk.I Matilda and 16 tanks Mk.II Matilda II. This battle received fame due to the fact that the Germans used 88 mm Flak 18 antiaircraft guns in an antitank gun role for the first time. Subsequently, the British used the Tank, Infantry, Mk.II in North Africa where the Matilda earned its nickname ‘Queen of the Desert’. The Mk.II tanks (basically the Matilda III and IV variants) were supplied to the USSR under the Lend-Lease Act. 
Obviously, the Tank, Infantry, Mk.II was an important milestone in the history of British tank engineering. The British managed to develop a tank with powerful armor and armament, capable of destroyingall types of enemy tanks (at the early stage of war)while remaining basically immune to enemy fire. At the same time some flaws were obvious. The 2-pounder gun lacked high-explosive capacity which translated into a weak performance against enemy infantry. This was partly recompensed by the presence of the CS variants equipped with a 76 mm OQF Mk.I howitzer. Service in the Red Army revealed another downside of the tanks: dirt accumulating between the ‘skirt’ panel and the tracks froze up in cold temperatures, clogging the suspension of the tank. The key problem of the Tank, Infantry, Mk.II was that it was nearly impossible to modernize, especially to replace its gun with a more powerful model.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/uk/a15_(valentine_ii)]
In February 1938, the Vickers-Armstrong corporation submitted to the War Office a new infantry tank design. This project was developed on its own initiative and it was the Vulcan Foundry Co, not Vickers-Armstrong, which received the contract for development of the Tank, Infantry, Mk.II Matilda Senior. The new tank was based on the Cruiser Tank Mk.I/II, from which it borrowed the running gear. The Vickers-Armstrong design envisioned a combat vehicle with a weight of not more than 16 tons (as opposed to the weight of the Tank, Infantry, Mk.II Matilda II, which was 26.5 tons), a 40 mm OQF Mk.IX gun and a 7.92 mm BESA coaxial machine. 
Although the design was already submitted in February 1938, it was not until May 1940 that the first prototype of the tank under the designation the Tank, Infantry, Mk.III Valentine was realized. The main reason for the delay was that the two-man turret was considered to be too small.The first 350 tanks were equipped with AEC A189 gasoline liquid-cooled engines. The models, later designates as the Valentine II, used the AEC A190 diesel engines. Some 700 units were produced. These tanks were easily recognizable due to a distinctive pistol port on the left side of the turret. The Valentine IV, VI and VII variants which came into production later differed from the Valentine II by the built-in engine only. In total, 8,275 tanks of the Tank, Infantry, Mk.III Valentine family were manufactured from 1940 to 1944, in the UK and also in Canada. The Valentine became Britain’s most produced tank. 
Ironically, it was not the British but the Soviet Army where the highest number of Valentine tanks served. The USSR received 3,332 tanks under the Lend-Lease Act. It is worth mentioning that the first Valentines got to the frontline in November 1941 right in time to be used in the Battle of Moscow. Various Valentine models served in the Soviet Army until the end of the war.
The Valentine proved to be a rather controversial vehicle. The lack of high-explosive shells, a common weakness for all British tanks equipped with 2-pdr and 6-pdr guns, hampered greatly the Valentine’s performance in fighting enemy infantry. Other serious faults included high vulnerability of its running gear as well as the small crew compartment. On the other hand, for a light tank, which the Valentine was in fact, the armor was fairly good and the 40 mm ROQF Mk.IX gun was comparable to 45 mm Soviet guns installed on the T-70. If seen as a light tank, the Valentine was probably one of the best tanks in its class.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/uk/a22f_(churchill_vii)]
In December 1939 the company Harland and Wolff received a contract for the design of a new tank as replacement for the Tank, Infantry, Mk.II Matilda II. The tank doctrine proposed by the British General Staff was based on the experience derived from World War I battles. As such it was proposed to redesign the famous British ‘diamond-shaped’ tanks with tracks running around the hull. The only difference was that now the turret and the front hull superstructure and not the side sponsons were supposed to carry armament. 
By summer of 1940 a prototype of the tank was designed, designated A20. Tests showed that the version had a series of downsides and eventually the company Vauxhall continued working on the ‘trench warfare tank’. In June 1941 the first series was manufactured. They received the designation Tank, Infantry, Mk.IV Churchill and the specification number A22. The first models of the Tank, Infantry, Mk.IV had a host of faults and broke down often. This inspired a saying by Winston Churchill, ”this tank has even more flaws than myself!”. The Churchill VII became the best model of the Tank, Infantry, Mk.IV, being also the heaviest and best protected British tank. Some 5,640 machines belonging to the Tank, Infantry, Mk.IV family were manufactured.
The Churchill was a controversial tank. Designed for positional warfare its only real advantage was its thick armor. The tracks running over the entire hull suggested good offroad capacity especially vs. obstacles such as trenches, but were extremely vulnerable at the same time. The extremely high position of the tracks greatly limited to the field of view of the co-driver and the gunner. However, the Churchill VII was the only British mass produced tank fully justifying its classification as ‘infantry’ tank. The standard ammunition load for the 75 mm ROQF Mk.V gun included high-explosive as well as armor-piercing shells. 

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/uk/a27m_(cromwell_iv)]
The history of the Cruiser Tank Mk.VIII Cromwell began in January 1941 when the project to desgin a replacement for the Cruiser Tank Mk.VI Crusader was approved. The prototype received the designation A24 and the name Cruiser Tank Mk.VII Cavalier in January 1942. Trials proved that the machine and especially its engine, a modification of the Liberty aircraft engine, were far from reliable. On the base of the Cavalier a new Cruiser Tank Mk.VIII Centaur (А27L) was designed to become an improved version of its predecessor. In total 3,134 Centaur tanks were manufactured but they hardly saw combat action in their original design.
In January 1943 the first tanks belonging to the Cruiser Tank Mk.VIII Cromwell family left the workshops of Birmingham Railway Carriage And Wagon Company. They were the Cruiser Tanks Mk.VIII Centaur equipped with Rolls Royce Meteor engines. Unlike the prototypes the Cromwell (A27M) received no complaints on reliability and became the main type of cruiser tanks used by British troops in 1944-45. The first vehicles later to receive the name Cromwell I were equipped with 6-pounder guns. The main variant, the Cromwell IV, was armed with a 75 mm ROQF Mk. V gun. In total 1,070 tanks of this type were manufactured and part of the Cruiser Tanks Mk.VIII Centaur were upgraded to Cromwell standard.
The Cromwell IV became the first ‘cruiser’ tank which was a real success. In line with the cruiser tank concept their main advantage was not thick armor but their maneuverability. The 75 mm gun was powerful enough to disable Pz.Kpfw.IV tanks, but the Panthers and even more so the Tigers were extremely dangerous rivals for the Cromwell IV. In general, the Cruiser Tank Mk.VIII Cromwell proved to be a fairly good medium tank and upgrading its design gave birth to the Cruiser Tank Comet, the best example of British wartime tank engineering.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/uk/a30_(challenger_i)]
In May 1942, Birmingham Carriage & Wagon Company began to develop a tank destroyer based on the Cruiser Tank Mk.VIII Cromwell. It was suggested to use the 76 mm 17-pdr OQF Mk.II gun, a conversion of the 17-pdr antitank gun, as the main armament. The new tank had a gun with a big breech block, which resulted in a much larger turret than that of the Cromwell, and also the tank’s hull was lengthened. A slight modification was made to the chassis – a sixth bogie wheel was added. The resulting version was designated as Cruiser Tank Mk.I Challenger. The total number of the Challengers produced reached 200.
Basically, the Challenger was not a tank in its traditional understanding. It was a special tank destroyer that differed from the German Jagdpanzer IV/70 and Jagdpanther only by the presence of a turret. The relatively small number of units manufactured points to the fact that the concept was far from perfect. A much simpler concept was to equip M4 Sherman tanks with the same 17-pounder gun, which is exactly what the British did in the end. This was the birth of the Sherman Firefly tank.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/uk/a34_(comet_i)]
In May 1943 the company Leyland started developing a new cruiser tank. It was based on the design of the Tank, Cruiser, Cromwell, Mk.VIII. The first prototype with the name Tank Comet and the designation number A34 was ready in February 1944. As opposed to the tanks of the Cavalier-Centaur-Cromwell series, the Comet was not an upgrade but an entirely new tank although its design included up to 40 percent Cromwell parts. Its most notable difference was the turret with a mounted 77 mm OQF Mk.II gun. This gun was a conversion from the 17-pounder antitank gun. Serial production of the Tank, Cruiser, Comet began in September 1944, and A total 1,200 units were produced.
Undoubtedly, the Comet was the most successful British tank of World War 2. Although inferior to enemy tanks in armor protection, the Comet enjoyed superiority in maneuverability. An AP shell the from 77mm OQF Mk.II gun could penetrate a 124 mm thick armored sheet from a distance of 1 kilometer. The British nevercould not take full advantage of their new tank as the war came to an end.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/usa/m24_(chaffee)]
When the first M5 Light Tanks started to roll off the assembly line, it was already clear that these vehicles needed a replacement. The development of a tank capable to replace the M3/M5 Light Tank started back in January 1941 and consequently several T7 family prototypes were developed. Since demands to armor protection and armament were continuously increasing, the final version of the new tank weighed as much as 25 tons and received the designation M7 Light Tank. As the M4 Medium Tank was already in production by that time, this vehicled remained a pilot model forever.
In April 1943, Cadillac Co. which by that time had experience in producing the M5 Light Tank, began to develop a new generation lighttank. The prototype of the T24 which emerged in October of the same year was strikingly different from the preceding light tanks. The design of the T24 was based on that of the tank destroyer M18 Hellcat, from which the machine borrowed its running gear. The most unusual component of the T24 was the 75 mm М6 gun, a conversion of a gun originally intended for equipping the B-25 G/H medium bombers. The gun’s main advantage was a compact recoil system. As for the power plant, the proven scheme of twin Cadillac V8 engines was used. To keep the gross weight of the T24 within reasonable limits for a light tank the designers had to sacrifice armor: its thickness was only 13-25 mm. The serial production of the tank with the designation M24 Light Tank and the name General Chaffee began in April 1944, and some 4,731 units were manufactured in total.
The doctrine for usage of the M24 Light Tank had much in common with that of the tank destroyer M18 Hellcat. Despite a weak armor, the M24 boasted agility and a powerful armament. Precisely these features make many people consider the M24 as the best light tank of World War II. These ssuccessful technical solutions contributed to a long combat service of the М24: some countries still use tanks of this type up to date. 

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/usa/m3_(lee)]
In 1939 the first mass produced American medium tankwas the M2, developed on the basis of the T5 pilot design. The faceted turret of the M2 and the later M2A1 housed its main armament consisting of a 37 mm M6 gun. In total 126 М2 and 92 М2А1 were built. The beginning of World War II proved quickly that the design of the M2/M2A1 had become outdated. The Army needed a new tank with better armor and a more powerful gun. 
In March 1941 the vehicle which was to become one of the most unusual tanks of World War II left the assembly line of the Rock Island Arsenal facility. Its predecessor was the pilot model T5E2 with a 75 mm howitzer installed in the right hull front plate. Based on the М2 the designers developed an absolutely new hull as well as a new turret. A sponson with a 75 mm M2 gun (later the M3 gun) was built into the front right hull. A second 37 mm gun was mounted on the turret.
Production of the tank with the designation M3 Medium Tank began in June 1941. The M3 Medium Tank is also known as General Lee (or simply Lee) a name mainly used by the British. Eventually, 6,258 M3 Medium Tanks were manufactured with 4,924 of them being M3 modifications. Inaddition to the American Army, the M3 Medium was supplied to the United Kingdom (2,877 units) and the USSR (1,386 units). On request by the British, the M3 General Grant was developed on the basis of the M3 Medium Tank with a different turret design. 
Despite its unusual design the M3 Medium Tank was a pretty good tank for its time. In the British Army where the M3 Grant appeared in the second half of 1941, the tank received positive reviews due to its powerful guns, fairly thick armor and most importantly its reliability. It is interesting that the full name of the British version of the M3 Medium Tank was Cruiser Tank Grant, and so the Cruiser Tank Mk.VI Crusader - known for its low reliability - was its counterpart. However, the M3 Medium Tank met quite the opposite attitude in the USSR where it wasnicknamed ‘a coffin for seven’. Such reference can to a large extent be explained by the fact that by the middle of 1942 the tank’s design was obsolete. Additionally, the T-34 and the KV-1 were superior to the American made tank in basically all aspects. 

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/usa/m4_(sherman)]
Oddly enough, production of the tank under the designation M4 Medium Tank started only  in July 1942, which was almost half a year after the M4A1 had already entered serial production. The only tank to leave the assembly line after the M4 was the M4A4 which had a different power plant and a lengthened hull. As far as its design is concerned, the M4 Medium Tank is closest to its predecessor, the M3 Medium Tank: it was equipped with the same Continental R975 C1 engine and had a similar shape of the rear hull. In the latest modifications the composite lid of the transmission compartment was replaced by an all-cast version. The latest M4 models were equipped with HVSS-type suspension. The total number of M4 Medium Tanks manufactured from July 1942 to January 1944 amounts to 6,742 vehicles.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/usa/m4a1_(sherman)]
In 1940 the development of the M3 Medium Tank coincided with the design of a more technically advanced machine. Like the M2 Medium Tank its main armament was installed on the turret, but this time it was planned to equip the tank with a 75 mm gun instead of 37 mm. In April a wooden model of the new tank was submitted to the Armament Committee and already in September 20 of the same year trials of the prototype under the designation T6 started at the Aberdeen testing grounds. Similar to the M3A1 Medium Tank the prototype had a cast hull, its armament included a 75 mm M2 gun, one coaxial and three 7.62 mm Browning M1919 machine guns. Following the results of the tests the design of the T6 saw a number of changes and in February 1942 production of the serial version started under the designation M4A1 Medium Tank. In the British Army, which was the first to use the M4A1 Medium Tank in combat the tank was referred to as the Sherman II. The first series had 3 machine guns but soon that number was reduced to one, andin later variants the composite transmission compartment lid was replaced with a fully cast version. Laters models were equipped with bogies on a HVSS type suspension. Some 6,281 tanks of that type were eventually manufactured. And the total production number for all tanks belonging to the M4 Medium Tank family reached 49,234 vehicles.
The M4 Medium Tanks turned out to be the most successful tanks manufactured in the US.  With good protection and a 75 mm gun, the M4A1 Medium Tank was quite a rival for German tanks. However, by the summer of 1943 it became obvious that the 75 mm M2/M3 gun already lacked the capacity to fight the latest versions of the Pz.Kpfw.IV as well as the Pz.Kpfw.V Panther and the Pz.Kpfw.VI Ausf.H1 Tiger tanks. 

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/usa/m4a2_(sherman)]
In April 1942 serial production of the M4A2 Medium Tank was launched. Unlike the M4A1, the hull of the M4A2 was fully cast, not welded. Compared to the M4A1 the frontal armor was reinforced.  From other M4 Medium Tanks the M4A2 with a welded hull differed by a slightly altered shape of the rear body and the design of the mufflers. The M4A2 Medium Tank was the only vehicle in the family equipped with a diesel engine: the GMC 6046. Later versions of the tank received an all-cast lid of the transmission compartment previously made of three bolted parts, a changed front hull plate and also new hatches for the driver and co-driver. The number of the M4A2 Medium Tanks produced totals 8,053.  

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/usa/m4a2_76_w_(sherman)]
In May 1944, Fisher Tank Arsenal began to manufacture a medium tank M4A2 equipped with a 76 mm (М4А2(76)W) gun. 2,894 tanks of this type were produced by May 1945. Another 21 tanks were manufactured by Pressed Steel Co.
The M4A2(76)W Medium Tanks with 76 mm gun received a turret of a different shape featuring a commander’s cupola. From August 1944 the design was enhanced with a round double hatch for the loader.
A power plant with 2 parallel twinned 6-cylinder GMC 6046 was installed with an output of 375 hp at 2,300 rpm. The tank was equipped with a powerful 76 mm М1А1 gun (model М1А2 with muzzle brake) with an AP shell muzzle velocity of 810 m/s. Installation of this gun enabled the Shermans to combat heavy German tanks.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/usa/m4a3_76_w_(sherman)]
The campaigns in Tunisia and Italy revealed that the 75 mm M3 gun lacked the capability to efficiently fight the newest German tanks Pz.Kpfw.V and Pz.Kpfw.VI as well as the latest versions of the Pz.Kpfw.IV. There was a need for a new modification of the M4 Medium tank equipped with a more powerful gun. The 76 mm M1 gun and its conversions, the M1A1 and the M1A2, were designed to meet these requirements. Aside from the gun, the ‘long-barrel’ M4 differed from the basic variant by the T23 turrets. Tanks equipped with T23 turrets and 76 mm guns were designated (76)W. The first tank to enter serial production in January 1944 was the M4A1(76)W. Production of the M4A3(76)W (called Sherman IVA in the British Army) began in March of the same year. The first 1,400 tanks carried the VVSS suspension; on the rest of the machines the HVSS suspension system was installed. A total of 4,542 units of this type were manufactured. 
From a distance of 1km an armor-piercing shell of the 76 mm M1A1 gun could penetrate 88 mm tick armor plates, which enabled the tank to combat German Pz.Kpfw.V Panther tanks. Additionally, HVAP sub-caliber shells were available for this gun, too, capable of penetrating 132 mm armor from the same distance or 99 mm armor from 2 km. Thus the advent of the M4A3(76)W and other M4 equipped with a 76 mm gun marked the arrival of a worthy rival for the German ‘steel beasts’.  

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/usa/m5a1_(stuart)]
The M5/M5A1 Light Tank was designed by the Cadillac Co. In October 1941 this company – a newcomer to tank engineering  - created its version of the M3A1 Light Tank with the key difference being a power plant consisting of twin Cadillac V8 automobile engines. The design with the designation M3A2E proved to be a success and entered service under the name M4 Light Tank. Although this tank was never put into mass production it became the basis for a more advanced tank, whose first models rolled off the assembly line in December 1942.
The tank officially referred to as M5 Light Tank differed substantially from the M3/M3A1 Light Tank line. Its hull was redesigned from scratch and only its running gear remained the same. Its shape slightly resembled the M3A3 Light Tank but unlike the predecessor the side plates were not sloped but positioned vertically. The tank was equipped with the twin-engine Cadillac V8В engine, proven on the M3A3E model. The turret was borrowed from the M3A1 Light Tank. A total of 2,074 M5 Light Tanks were manufactured. After short time already the M5 Light Tank was replaced on the assembly line by a more advanced model, the M5A1. It featured a different turret borrowed from the M3A3 Light Tank. In late M5A1 models the anti-aircraft machine gun was hidden in a special armored casing in the right-hand part of the turret. The M5A1 became the most mass produced version in the whole M3/M5 Light Tank family – some 6,810 tanks of this type were manufactured.
Although the first tanks of the M5/M5A1 family were manufactured already at the end of 1942 until the beginning of 1943, they were not used for combat until early 1944. By that time the 37 mm M6 gun was obviously out-dated and could serve for fighting enemy light-armored vehicles only. It was the gun which seriously limited the combat characteristics of the tank, even though its armor was far from being the thinnest (the front plate was 60 mm thick). Apart from the US Army, the M5/M5A1 Light Tanks were also used by the British. It is interesting that in the UK tanks of both modifications received the same designation, Stuart VI. Quite frequently tanks of this type were converted to armored troop carriers or reconnaissance vehicles: the conversion consisted in removing the turret and installing a large-caliber machine gun instead. Also the Howitzer Motor Carriage M8 HMC, also known as Scott, was developed on the basis of the M5/M5A1

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/ger/kv_1_ger]
In addition to trophy T-34, heavy KV tanks captured in working condition were used by Wehrmacht from the beginning of the war with the USSR. Some KV-1 tanks were sent to german factories and from the middle of 1942 they were sent back to the front, mainly to 1, 8 and 22 Pz.Div. Around 50 KV tanks were employed, say official german sources.
One of the most famous german regiments using KV tanks was PzAbt zBV-66 formed 30 May 1942 for abortive invasion of Malta. It had many rare vehicles, for example Pz - I Ausf F , PzKpfw - I Ausf J , PzKpfw - II Ausf F2 with 80mm front armor, KV-1, KV-2 and T-34 tanks.
Command turrets from PzKpfw - III/IV were installed on some KV tanks, in addition one tank was refitted with 75mm KwK-40 gun. Several heavy KV-2 tanks were sent to Germany in early period of war for research and propaganda, at least one of them remaind there until late war. Several sources indicate that this machine defended Krupp factory from american tanks. H.Euler in his book "Die Entscheidungschlacht an rein und Ruhr" mentions KV-1 captured by americans in April 1945.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/ger/t_34_mod_1941_ger]
German army captured many T-34/76 in 1941-1943 years, they were designated as Pz.Kpfw.747 T-34(r). There were several labels for various models: A (mod.1940), B (mod.1941), C (mod.1942), D / E / F (mod.1943). T-34(r) Ausf D (captured Т-34 mod. 42) was often called "Mickey-Mouse" because two round hatches in turret looked like it's ears while open.
During summer 1941 first captured T-34(r) were given to 1st, 8th and 11th panzer divisions, but they were not used on frontline because of high risk of friendly fire (gunners mostly relied on target silhouette instead of markings for identification). Later, to minimize such situations, large markings or swastikas were painted on sides and roofs of hull and turret of these tanks. They were also typically used in infantry formations to minimize possibility of own artillery fire at them.
Total of 300 T-34/76 were used by Whermacht ans SS units (both in frontline and occupational duties) - for example, 1st panzer regiment of 1st panzer division (15 October 1941 it had 6 T-34), 2nd PzDiv, 33rd PzRgt of 9th PzDiv, 7th PzRgt of 10th PzDiv, 11 PzDiv, 21st PzRgt of 20th PzDiv, 23rd PzDiv.
Formed for invasion of Malta in May 1942 Pz.Abt.zBV.66 had captured KV-1, KV-2 and T-34 in 2nd company. After disbanding of this battalion T-34 were transferred to 1st Ski Jaeger division, which was part of army group Center.
Elite panzer forces of Third Reich used T-34 too. Panzer Regiment of PzDiv "Grossdeutschland" had them until 1945.
After battle of Kharkov during spring 1943 (Manstein Kharkov Counteroffensive) 2nd SS panzer corps captured around 50 T-34 mod.1941-1942. 2nd PzDiv "Das Reich" received 25 of them and 3rd SS PzDiv "Totenkopf" got 22.
During summer 1943 T-34(r) were mostly used in tank destroyer units - 3 Panzer Jager Abteilung of 2nd PzDiv "Das Reich" had 25. "Das Reich" report from 4th July says about 18 functioning T-34(r) and 9 being repaired.
During battle of Kursk T-34(r) were used, in addition to SS units, in 11th PzRgt of 6 PzDiv (10 July - 4 tanks), several ones in 128th Pz.Jg.Abt of 23rd PzDiv. Army group Center had 22 T-34(r) total in July 1943 and army group South 28.
23rd PzDiv used captured T-34 tanks until the end of the war. Several T-34(r) had italian crews. 24 tanks were used by Mechislav Kaminsky brigade against belorussian partisans during September 1943. At the end of 1943 T-34(r) company was given to ROA of general Vlasov.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/rus/a15_(valentine_ii)_rus]
USSR received 3332 Valentines by lend-lease program, first ones arrived to the front lines in November 1941 and fought in Battle of Moscow. Various models of these tanks were used until the end of the war. 2394 Valentines were sent to USSR by Great Britain and 1388 by Canada. There were equpped with 40mm or 57mm guns.
These tanks fought almost in all regions. For example, they were used in Trans-Caucasus front, in 19th tank corps of South front (4th Ukrainian front after 20 October 1943) and played a major role in Melitopol offensive and then in liberation of Crimea. Valentines also were actively used in mostly static battles in West and Kalinin fronts up to beginning of 1944.
Valentines were main tanks of cavalry corps until the end of the war, cavalrymen liked their maneouverability. They were also given to many motorcycle battalions and separate motorcycle regiments (these regiments had 10 T-34 or 10 Valentine IX during late war). In general, Valentine was the most popular of british ta

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/rus/a12_(matilda_ii)_rus]
1084 Matildas MkII were sent to USSR from Great Britain, while only 918 arrived safely.
During 1941 and 1942 Matilda was the most 'tough' tank, even more than KV - only 88mm shells of german AA gun could kill it, it was invulnerable to AT or tank guns fire. It's gun power was close to soviet 45mm gun and, like it, Matilda's gun showed so-so performance until summer 1942. Main drawback of Matildas was the lack of HE shells for it's 40mm gun.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/rus/m3_(lee)_rus]
Total of 1386 M3 tanks were sent to USSR.
Soviet tankers met them without enthusiasm. M3's armor was already unsatisfactory in summer 1942 because of 75mm german tank guns and speed, obscurity and manoeuverability were needed. But high, with poor passability on russian roads and low power engine which was picky for oil and fuel, M3 tanks caused only frustration. Their crews tried to swap them for familiar T-34 tanks by any means possible.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/rus/m4a2_(sherman)_rus]
Soviet tankers liked Sherman. While it was next best in their opinion after T-34 in terms of armor and weaponry, it was much more ergonomical, had more spacious turret and many handy little things which helped daily service a lot. With arrival of late model Shermans which had new 76mm guns with high-quality ammo (it was imported from USA too) they eclipsed even new T-34 with 85mm gun by ant-tank capabilities. Sherman's armor was thickier than T-34 armor, but less hard, and armor effectiveness of both tanks was almost equal, while more ductile armor of Sherman caused less internal spalling in case of almost-penetrations. It's main drawback was high centre of mass which caused frequent turnovers.
American sources indicate that a total of 1990 75mm Shermans and 2073 76mm Shermans were sent to USSR. In May 1945 Red Army received some quantity of tanks with horizontal suspension, they participated in destruction of Kvantun japan army.
Shermans participated in liberation of Ukraine, Belorussia, Poland, Chekhoslovakia and Austria; some of them were used in assault on Berlin itself.

