[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/rus/pz_iiif_rus]
During 1941-1942 years Red Army captured large numbers of german Pz.Kpfw III , Pz.Kpfw IV and Pz.Kpfw 38(t) tanks. Captured tanks were mostly used in West and North-Caucasus fronts because these frontlines were mostly static, didn't require long marches and this helped to stretch the overhaul period of their foreign engines which were difficult to service. Moreover, there was Moscow in the rear of West front with it's industrial capacity, where these tanks could be repaired.
West front had entire formations armed with these tanks. Beginning from the spring and to the end of 1942 there were two battalions called 'separate tank battalions letter "B" in the front orders. One of them was part of 31st Army (it had 9 T-60 and 19 german tanks, mainly Pz.III and Pz.IV on 1 August 1942), while the other was given to 20th Army (7 Pz. Kpfw. IV, 12 Pz. Kpfw. III, 2 «Artshturm» (StuG III) and 10 38(t) on 1 August 1942). Battalion of 20th Army was called "Nebylov battalion" by the name of it's commander major Nebylov.
Most complete information is available for Nort-Caucasus (Trans-Caucasus) front where soviet forces defeated 13th panzer division during October and November 1942 and captured part of it's equipment. This allowed to equip several tank units with german vehicles. 175th separate tank battalion had three StuG III SPGs, 151st tank brigade during 24 March 1943 received 2nd battalion fully equipped with trophies: 3 Pz. Kpfw. IV, 5 Pz. Kpfw. III and 1 Pz. Kpfw. II. This battalion together with brigade participated in fighting as part of 37th Army. 266th separate tank battalion, which also fought in that area, had 4 Pz. III in addition to soviet tanks.
62nd and 75th separate tank battalions in 56th Army of North-Caucasus front had captured vehicles too.

