[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/rus/pz_vg_(panther)_rus]
It's widely known that new german Pz. Kpfw. V «Panther» tanks seen first action on southern face of Kursk salient duing July 1943. It's interesting that one of them was captured and used by Red Army as early as 5 August in offensive in Belgorod area, but there are no information about it's performance.
One captured «Panther» was briefly used by tankers of 59th separate tank regiment during Autumn 1943. Veterans say, that "during the attack of our tanks all enemy fire was focused on trophy «Pantera»".
Russian tankers were pleased with «Panther» 75mm KwK-42 main gun: it's ballistic characteristics allowed them to destroy enemy tanks at distances beyound the reach of all soviet tank and anti-tank guns. It seems it was the reason for order of GBTU KA (Main Tank Department of Red Army) to concentrate functioning captured «Panthers» into special tank destroyer units and use them in areas where the threat of enemy tanks was maximal. In the same time "Brief manual of using captured tank T-V ("Pantera")" was printed. During January 1944 in the fights near Zhitomir units of 3rd Guards tank army captured many damaged german tanks. By order of second-in-command of this army general-major Y. Solovyev two platoons of most experienced repair mechanics were formed in 41st and 148th repair battalions; they managed to restore four T-4 and one T-5 «Pantera» quickly. After several days soviet "Pantera" destroyed enemy "Tiger" tank in a fight in Zherebka area.
Captured «Panther» tanks were in use by Red Army until the end of the war, usually episodically and in small numbers. For example, during repulsing german offensive in lake Balaton area during March 1945, 991th self-propelled artillery regiment under the command of colonel Gordeev (46th Army of 3rd Ukrainian front) was equipped with 3 trophy «Panthers» in addition to 16 SU-76.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/ger/t_34_85_ger]
Relatively many T-34-85 were captured and used by Third Reich in middle and late war on East front. Most of them were used in battles in Eastern Prussia and Chekhoslovakia in 1945.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/ger/m3_(lee)_ger]
German forces used small quantity of captured american M3 and M4 tanks on East and West fronts during 1943-1945.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/ger/m4a2_(sherman)_ger]
German forces used small quantity of captured american M3 and M4 tanks on East and West fronts during 1943-1945.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/uk/Sherman_IC]
M4 and M4 Composite Hull (with cast front hull, also known as Sherman Hybrid), M4A1 and M4A4 Sherman variants were chosen to be rearmed with 17pdr gun. Initial order for 2100 units was issued by War Ministry in January 1944. Each tank platoon should have had two such tanks and these rearmed vehicles were intended to be used in British, Canadian and Polish tank regiments in Europe. Rearming works were carried out in Royal war factory in Leeds and Woolwich arsenal near London. 699 tanks were rearmed before 31st July 1944.
They were baptized by fire in Normandy, were they received nickname ‘Firefly’. It’s difficult to guess why battle tank received such a name, maybe because ‘Firefly’ means not only glowing insect, but also ‘dark yellowish-red color’. It’s possible that fire flash of 17-pdr was of this color.
All regiments of British tank divisions and brigades had Shermans in action at ’D’ day (excluding 7th tank division and recon regiments of 11th and Guards tank divisions which had Cromwells and army tank brigades armed with Churchills). All these regiments had 12 Fireflies each. They could be easily separated from ordinary Shermans by radio box and long gun barrel with pear-shaped muzzle brake.
At 24 July 1944 (while Normandy battle ) line tank regiments of 21st army group (His Majesty forces on Western Europe) had 288 Sherman Firefly tanks, and their number increased to 728 by the end of the year.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/uk/Sherman_I]
First 300 M4A1 and several M4A2 tanks arrived to North Africa at August – September 1942. Immediately after arrival “Shermans” were sent to British works in Tel-al-Kabir and El-Abassiya, where they were rearmed for the specific theater conditions and British army regulations.
There were around 250 Sherman tanks in first line of tank divisions of 8th army at 23rd October 1942 during El-Alamein battle. Soon Shermans of various modifications became main battle tanks of British army, gradually they took the place of other British and American vehicles. By rearming some M4 and M4A4 tanks with 17-pdr gun with initial round speed of 908m/s British made powerful modifications Sherman IC and Sherman VC, better known as Sherman Firefly.
All regiments of British tank divisions and brigades had Shermans in action at ’D’ day (excluding 7th tank division and recon regiments of 11th and Guards tank divisions which had Cromwells and army tank brigades armed with Churchills), including 600 Sherman Fireflies (25 in each tank regiment).
Shermans were also actively used in Italy by the British. In addition to battle tanks, British received many special purpose Sherman-based vehicles (some variants they developed themselves).
 
[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/ger/pz_iiijk]
Pz.Kpfw.III Ausf.J was developed in March 1941 and produced by Daimler-Benz, Alkett, MAN, Wegmann, Henschel, MNH and MIAG companies. 2616 tanks of this type were made before July 1942 (hull numbers 68001-69100 and 72001-74100). Ausf. J had much better armor (10-50mm), new driver visor Fahrersehklappe 50 and ball and socket joint (Kugelblende 50) for 7,92mm MG34. Hatches of new type and new air inlets were installed in fore body. Beginning from April 1942 new 20mm cell armored plates were added to main gun mantle and front hull.
1549 tanks made during time frame March 1941 – July 1942 were armed with 50mm KwK 38 L/42 tank guns and two 7.92mm machineguns (PzKpfw III Ausf J / Sd.Kfz.141), while 1067 tanks PzKpfw III Ausf J / Sd.Kfz.141/1 made between December 1941 and July 1942 were armed with 50mm KwK 39 L/60 tank guns and two 7.92mm machineguns. The only difference between these two types was main gun type and ammunition reserve (84 and 99 rounds).
When the British encountered these Panzer III Ausf J with 50mm KwK 39 L/60 guns in North Africa, they called them "Mark III Special". Installation of new 50mm gun in place of old 37mm gun was done in proper time, but it was still inadequate for combating American Shermans and Soviet T-34/76. There were also bold, but unsuccessful attempt of installing Panzer IV Ausf G turret onto PzIII Ausf J body.
81 command tanks Panzerbefehlswagen III mit 5cm KwK L/42 / Sd.Kfz.141 were made in August - November 1942, and additional 104 Ausf J were converted to command variant during March – September 1943. They were copies of Ausf J with additional radio equipment and periscope, but had lesser inner space and lower ammunition reserve (75 rounds).

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/rus/is_1]
IS-1 heavy tank was developed in design bureau of Kirov factory in Chelyabinsk under direction of Zh. Y. Kotin in second half of 1942. It was based on KV-13 (as well as IS-2).
IS-1 had 76mm gun, while IS-2 was armed with 122mm howitzer-gun. First experimental IS prototypes had 5-rollers suspension as well as KV-13, and looked much like it.
First IS-1 variant with 85mm gun D-5T (IS-85 or “Object 237”) was developed during Summer 1943 in the same design bureau under direction of  lead designer N.F. Shamshurin. It was necessary two add two more rollers to suspension and more powerful engine to cope with increased weight of armament. It was designated IS-1 (or IS-85) andofficially added to Soviet arsenal at 7th August by order of GKO (State Defense Committee).
It weighted 44 tons, not much more than KV, but had thicker armor. Turret, front hull, turret support and rear were cast. IS-1 hull width was 18cm smaller than KV-1S width thanks to installation of smaller planetary rotation mechanisms.
Production of IS-1 tanks was cancelled in the beginning of 1944.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/ger/pz_iiin]
Tanks of last Pz. III production variant N had the same turret and hull as L (47 hulls and turrets used) and M variants (213 hulls and turrets used). The main difference between N and precious series was 75mm short-barreled KwK 37 L/24 tank gun with ammunition reserve of 64 rounds, which was previously installed in Pz.Kpfw.IV tanks from A to F1. Pz. III N had different gun mantlet and integral command turret hatch. Sighting-slit to the right side of the gun was removed. It was possible to attach 30mm armored sheets to the all sides of the tank, but this resulted in severe speed reduction. 90mm smoke dischargers NbKWg were installed on both sides of the turret.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/ger/pz_ivf1]
Pz-IV ausf F modification was produced from April 1941 to March 1942 by companies “Krupp-Gruson”, “Vomag” и “Nibelungenwerke”, total 487 tanks were made. It was developed based on experience of using previous Pz. IV variants in Poland and France. Armor thickness was again increased to 50mm (hull and turret fronts) and 30mm (sides). Single-winged hatches in turret sides were replaced with double-winged and front hull became straight again. Designers kept the MG, but it was installed into ball and socket joint Kugelblende 50. Since tank mass increased by 48% (compared to Ausf. E), new 400mm wide tracks were introduced instead of earlier 360mm.
Additional air inlets were added to engine compartment roof and to transmission hatches, placing and design of mufflers of engine and turret traverse motor was changed.
All previous Pz. IV modifications were armed with short-barreled 75mm tank gun with initial AP round velocity of only 385m/s, which was inadequate for combating British “Matilda” and Soviet T-34 and KV tanks. After producing 462 Pz. IV Ausf. F their production was halted for one month and tank design was significantly changed: mainly, new gun 75mm KwK 40 developed by “Krupp” and “Rheinmetall” companies was installed, which could propel AP round to initial speed of 770m/s. Production of these guns started at March 1942, and 4th April tank with new gun was shown to Hitler, after that the production was resumed. Tanks with short-barreled cannons were designated F1, and with long-barreled ones F2.
 
[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/ger/Pz_IIIF_Spat]
Order for development of medium tank was issued in 1934. It should have had mass up to 15 tons and had one 37mm gun and three 7.92 machineguns. This project was called Zugfuhrerwagen – company commander vehicle – because of secrecy: in fact this vehicle was developed as main battle tank for Reichswehr and later Wehrmacht, each tank battalion should have had three companies of these “company commander vehicles”.
Daimler-Benz design was selected as the best one out of designs developed by four companies, it was called Panzerkampfwagen III (Sd.Kfz.141). First 10, experimental tanks Pz.Kpfw.III Ausf.A were made in 1936, they had suspension with 5 rollers for each side, each roller had separate spring suspension. Next two series, Ausf. B and Ausf.C (12 and 15 tanks made) were equipped with new suspension system with 8 rollers at each side with leaf springs.
Next series, Ausf. D (30 tanks) still had complex and expensive leaf-spring suspension, but it was more fitting for battle conditions nonetheless. Armor thickness was increased and tank mass increased too to 19.8 tons.
First mass produced variant of Pz. III was Ausf. E (96 tanks), these tanks were equipped with torsion suspension (developed by Ferdinand Porsche). New tanks also had new engine, new double-winged hatches on turret sides, ball and socket joint for machinegun was changed.
Production of new series, Pz.Kpfw.III Ausf.F (435 produced), was started at September 1939, these tanks had air intakes for brakes cooling installed of front hull. Last 100 tanks were armed with 50mm Kw.K 38 L/42 tank gun installed in new gun mantle (one of the coaxial machine guns was removed). All tanks of series E and F were rearmed in the same way later.

