[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/ger/pz_iiil]
Production of new variant – Ausf L (9-Serie) – was started in June 1942. It was manufactured by compaines Daimler-Benz, Alkett, Wegmann, MAN, Henschel, MNH and MIAG. 653 such tanks were made before December 1942 (chassis numbers 74101- 75500). They were armed with 50mm KwK 39 L/60 tank guns and two 7.92mm MG34 machineguns. Ausf L tanks looked much like late Ausf J models because they were based on them, the main difference was new torsion gun bob, which replaced the old standard spring one. Front hull armor thickness was increased from 37 to 50mm, additional 20mm thick armored cell sheets were installed onto front hull and, usually, on gun mantle. Rear hull construction was simplified (air inlets and hatches), and during initial production evacuation hatches on the hull were removed together with looking slit for loader in the gun mantle and small hatches on turret sides. Special system for transferring heated engine coolant to another tank was also installed on Ausf L. One of the tanks was armed with experimental 75/55mm KwK0725 tank gun with wedge-shaped barrel canal, it was designated PzKpfw III Ausf L mit Waffe 0725. Tanks which were sent to North Africa were equipped with additional air filters, modified oil filters and fan reduction gears with different gear-ratio, they were designated Ausf L(Tr). Ausf L was the first Panzer III, on which commander cupola anti-air capable machinegun was installed (Fliegerbeschussgerat 41/42), this became a standard for all produced Panzer III tanks (older models were refitted with these machineguns.) Many Ausf. L tanks were also equipped with hull and turret 5mm Schurzen (armored sheets).
 
[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/rus/t_34_57_mod_1941]
3 June 1940 head of Defense Committee S. Timoshenko sent the staff report about inadequate weapon power of new T-34 and KV tanks and other promising tanks in development to the Central Committee of Communist Party and SNK (Council of People Commissars) of USSR and 27 June special conference of SNK and Central Committee of Communist Party took place regarding this matter. It was agreed that 45mm tank guns are too weak and unpromising, new 55-60mm tank guns should be developed instead.
Experimental prototype of new 57mm gun was made and tests begun in the early December. Factory tests on field gun-carriage took place from December to end of March 1941 and in April it was installed into T-34 for field testing, which revealed short barrel life and low grouping of shots. In July 1941 elaborated gun, designated as ZIS-4, was again installed into T-34 and new tests took place on Sophrino firing range. They were successful, but technology of making such long barrels was extremely expensive and the new gun was approved only because need for powerful anti-tank guns was considered paramount. These guns was intended for installing on special “tanks-destroyers” T-34-57 and mass production of ZIS-4 was started on factory #92 in the middle of July 1941, as ordered by NKV (People Commissariat of Weapons).
Т-34-57 saw action in Battle for Moscow. For example, 21st tank brigade formed in Vladimir had 10 of these tanks. At 14th October tank brigade was unloaded on rail station Demidovo and on the following day it was ordered to advance on Turchinovo-Pushkino-Troyanovo route to make flank attack into group of German forces near Kalinin. These fights uncovered new heroes: tank under command of “politruk” (ideology officer) Gmyrya arrived at Volokolamsk highway when large column of German cars and infantry was moving along it. The tank devastated entire column (2-3km long!), then it rushed in German airfield and destroyed heavy bomber using main gun. After that tank was knocked out by fire from AT and plane guns, but Gmyrya and his sergeant Ischenko fought their way through to Soviet forces. During 4 days fighting, brigade destroyed 3 headquarters, up to 1000 soldiers, 34 tanks, 210 cars, 25 AT guns, 6 “thermite guns” and others. Tank regiment commander of this brigade, Hero of the Soviet Union major Lukin and 1st tank battalion commander, Hero of the Soviet Union captain Abigalov died in these fights. All T-34-57 were lost before 25th November.


[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/rus/kv_1_f32]
During Autumn 1938 Leningrad Kirov Factory (LKZ) was ordered to design a heavy multi-turreted tank of second generation to replace T-35. It was quickly realized that specified conditions (maximum mass 60 tons, 60mm armor thickness) limit number of turrets to 2 maximum. Two prototypes, SMK and T-100 were built and tested in battle in Finnish 1939-1940 Winter war. Both of them were not mass-produced. Simultaneously with 2-turret tanks single turret variant was developed and designated KV (Klim Voroshilov). It was based on SMK design, but constructors decreased hull dimensions considerably, increasing armor thickness. KV-1 prototype, U-0, had two guns: 45mm tank gun mod.1934 and 76mm tank gun L-11. During trials which begun in September 1939 45mm gun was removed and DT machinegun was installed instead, with this armament U-0 was battle-tested in Winter war. First tank of initial series, U-2, was released for army testing in February 1940.
KV tanks of initial series had chamfered welded turrets, while on mass produced ones more simple cut welded turrets were fitted. 76mm L-11 tank guns were installed on KV tanks until December 1940 (142 tanks were made). Contrary to popular opinion that these tanks didn't see combat, there are photos which prove they did. Beginning in January 1941, new 76.2mm F-32 tank guns with better ballistics were installed in KV tanks (now called KV-1), this variant became most numerous when the war broke out. 423 tanks were made before 1st July 1941 on both LTZ and ChTZ (Chelyabinsk Tractor Factory). Another new gun, 76mm ZiS-5, was used in KV-1 tanks during Autumn 1941. Because of armor plates shortage, KV-1 tanks with cast turrets were mass-produced along with KV-1 with welded turrets starting in January 1942.
KV-1 was the best heavy tank in the world until Pz.Kpfw.VI Ausf.E Tiger was made. Contrary to other heavy tanks of it's time, KV-1 had not only excellent armor, but a good weaponry as well, enabling it to combat enemy infantry and armor effectively. Unfortunately, hasty adoption into service resulted in poor reliability of the tank, especially of it's chassis. Large percentage of KV-1 was lost because of technical difficulties, in addition Red Army lacked trained crews. Nevertheless, with good crew KV-1 was a formidable weapon, during 1941 Germans could effectively use only 88mm Flak 18/36 and 50mm AT guns Pak 38 against it.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/ger/pz_iiie]
In 1934 the Army Ordnance Department ordered the development of a medium tank. The order required that the tank should have a combat weight of 15 tons and its armament should consist of a 37 mm gun and three 7.92 mm machine guns. The project was entitled Zugfuhrerwagen, i.e. squad commander vehicle. This name was chosen to keep the project a secret: in fact the Zugfuhrerwagen was developed as the main tank of the Reichswehr (and later the Wehrmacht). According to the organizational chart, each tank battalion was to include three squads of “squad commander vehicles.” 
Four firms took part in the contest for the development, and the design by Daimler-Benzwas finally chosen. By that time the tank was designated Panzerkampfwagen III and received the  official Wehrmacht designation Sd.Kfz.141. In 1936, 10 Pz.Kpfw.III Ausf.A tanks were produced, which were essentially trial vehicles. Their running gear featured five road wheels on either side, each wheel with an individual helical spring. The next two series, Ausf.B and Ausf.C (12 and 15 tanks respectively) featured a new running gear with eight road wheels on each side. The road wheels had leaf springs. In 1938 a new modification, Ausf.D, appeared and 30 such vehicles were produced. The tank still had a complex and expensive leaf spring suspension but this vehicle could was considered to be pretty much fit for combat conditions. The reinforced armor brought the tank weight up to 19.8 tons.
The Pz.Kpfw.III Ausf.E was the first real mass production model of the Pz.Kpfw.III series. This vehicle featured a torsion bar suspension designed by Ferdinand Porsche. The tank also had a new engine, two-piece side hatches installed in the turret, and a re-designed ball mount for the bow machine gun. The hull sides now had escape hatches. A total of 96 Pz.Kpfw.III Ausf.E tanks were produced.

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/ger/pz_iiil_2]
In June 1942 mass production of new Pz III variant has begun - Ausf L (9-Serie). It was produced by Daimler-Benz, Alkett, Wegmann, MAN, Henschel, MNH and MIAG. 653 of these tanks were made before December 1942 (chassis numbers 74101-75500). They were equipped with 50mm KwK 39 L/60 tank guns and 7.92mm MG34 machineguns. This variant looked like late Ausf J model, because Ausf L was it's modified version, the main difference between them was new torsion gun beam, which replaced standard spring gun return mechanism. Front turret armor was increased to 50mm (was 37mm), in addition 20mm cell armor sheets were installed on front hull, and, sometimes, on gun mantle. Rear hull equipment (air intakes and hatches) was simplified, loader's looking slit and hatches on turret sides were removed, new special system for transferring hot coolant from one engine to another was installed. One of Ausf L, designated PzKpfw III Ausf L mit Waffe 0725, was equipped with experimental 75/55mm cannon KwK0725 (it had cone-shaped bore).
Tanks intended for North Africa (Ausf L(Tr)) theatre had additional air filters, modified oil filters and fan reduction gears with another ratio.
Anti-air machinegun Fliegerbeschussgerat 41/42, installed on top of commander's cupola, first appeared on Ausf L tanks and then AA MGs became widespread on all Pz III models. Many Ausf L tanks had 5mm armored skirts on hull and turret (Schurzen).

[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/ger/pz_ivg]
Pz.Kpfw.IV Ausf.G (1687 units produced from May 1942 to April 1943) had not any principal differencies from F modification. The only improvement was two-chamber muzzle brake on the gun, in addition most of these tanks lacked observaton instruments in front hull to the right of the gun and in right turret side. Neverthless, there are no such instruments on most F2 tanks as well, judging by photos. Last 412 Ausf.G tanks were equipped with 75mm KwK 40 tank gun, barrel length 48 calibers. Special 1450-kg "Ostketten" tracks, additional 30mm front armor (for around 700 vehicles), and side Shurzen were used for late series of these tanks, making them almost undestinguishable from next Pz.IV variant - Ausf.H.
One of these tanks was re-equipped and became a prototype for "Hummel" self-propelled gun.

