[EncDescription_data/units/tanks/pol/renault_ft17_pol]
During April - May 1919, 1st tank regiment was formed in General Haller Polish army in France. It was based on former French 505th tank regiment and was armed with most advanced tanks of that times - Renault FT-17. Haller army, including tank regiment, returned to Poland in June 1919. Thanks to this, Poland became fourth country in the world (judging by amount of tanks).
During late twenties old machineguns were replaced by 7.92mm Hotchkiss wz.25 MGs (French installed new 7.5mm Chatellerault (Reibel) Mle.31 machineguns during thirties). Tanks with the new machineguns were unofficially called FT-31.
In 1939, before the war, Poland had 102 FT-17 light tanks, including 70 in 2nd armored battalion in Zhuravitse and 32 in two armored train battalions, were they were used as armored trolleys.
Battle efficiency of FT-17 tanks in 1939 was extremely low, because they were very slow and obsolete.

